<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Minister on Causes of Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rains and rising sea
levels in the Bay of Bengal are two major causes of the country's
prolonged flood this year, Water Resources Minister Abdur Razzaq
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Other causes of the flood include the effect of the weather
phenomenon La Nina, the reduction of flood plain because of
unplanned construction of roads, bridges, culverts and homesteads
and the rise of riverbeds due to siltation, Razzaq told Xinhua in
an exclusive interview.
</P>
<P>
"Bangladesh is a country where people are living with flood"
and "we need limited flood every year, as flood carries siltation
to the agricultural plain and makes the land fertile," he said.
</P>
<P>
But when there is too much water, it creates havoc for
agriculture and for the life and property of the people and is
harmful for the country's economic situation, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The flood this year lasts much longer than before and has
caused heavier losses. The minister estimated the loss this year
in the water resources sector alone at 150 million U.S. dollars
and the country's total loss at as high as 2.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the measures Bangladesh has taken or to be taken to prevent
and control flood, Razzaq listed construction of embankments,
river dredging and river taming.
</P>
<P>
The country's major flood facilities are around 500 embankments
along major rivers, dikes and a 250-meter-long barrage in
northeastern Bangladesh, he said.
</P>
<P>
As the country concluded a 30-year water sharing treaty with
India in 1996, it has become possible for Bangladesh to consider
the construction of a Ganges barrage within the country, both for
flood control and for storing water for the dry season, he said,
adding that the feasibility study of the project would start soon.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that river dredging is also very important, as
construction of embankments alone could not contain flooding
waters.
</P>
<P>
There is no reservoir in Bangladesh so far, but the government
has planned to construct big ponds, one for each of the 4,451
unions (townships) and for each village if possible, to store
drinking water, as the ground water level is dropping and is
believed to be arsenic-contaminated in many parts of the country,
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He said the government, which has drafted a national water
conservancy plan, has set up a flood forecasting and warning
center and an information gathering and distributing system to
increase flood awareness among the people and would construct
permanent flood shelters across the country.
</P>
<P>
He called on the international community, mainly Bangladesh's
donor countries and agencies and other friendly countries, for
help and cooperation in embankments building and river dredging
and taming in the low-lying country.
</P>
<P>
Forty-five of the country's 64 districts have been hit by flood
since the monsoon season began in the country in early July, with
more than 20.7 million people affected and a death toll of 451 so
far.
</P>
<P>
The flood has also damaged more than 227,000 hectares of crops,
more than 377,000 houses, 9,347 kilometers of roads, 4,121
kilometers of embankments, 4,652 bridges and culverts and 1,052
educational institutions, according to the Relief and Disaster
Management Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
