<HEADLINE> India Controls Mosquito-Borne Diseases With Curtain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Indian scientists at the
Malaria Research Center (MRC) here claimed to have controlled
mosquito-borne diseases in urban slum areas using curtains
impregnated with insecticide.
</P>
<P>
A two-year study by an MRC team found about 90-percent
reduction of disease-causing mosquitoes in a slum area in New
Delhi, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
PTI quoted team leader M. A. Ansari as saying curtains coated
with the insecticide, deltamethrin, is deadly against aedes
aegypti, the mosquito species causing dengue, as well as anopheles
stephensi and anopheles culicifacies, two well-known malaria
vectors.
</P>
<P>
Ansari said the insecticide-coated curtains could kill
mosquitoes within 15 minutes and also protect people from
cockroaches, house-flies and bed-bugs.
</P>
<P>
The effect of the insecticide lasts for nine weeks, after which
it can be re-sprayed. Only 25 milligrams of deltamethrin is
required to coat the curtain on both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
