<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Urges No Retreat From Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Foreign Minister S
Jayakumar has called upon developing countries to learn to cope
with the onslaught of globalization and not withdraw from the
"inexorable" process.
</P>
<P>
In a statement made at the 12th Summit of the Non-Aligned
Movement in Durban, South Africa, and released here by the
Singapore Foreign Ministry Thursday evening, Jayakumar called
globalization a clear irreversible force.
</P>
<P>
"The response to globalization should not be to withdraw
inward" and "instead we should do what we can to prepare and equip
our people to face the challenges arising from the inexorable
process of globalization, or else we will suffer higher adjustment
costs in the long run," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said it is wrong to place blame squarely
on globalization for the Asian financial crisis which he said "has
snowballed into a major financial crisis with swiftness and depth
of devastation that no one could have anticipated."
</P>
<P>
Jayakumar stressed, "It was the forces of globalization that
gave the developing countries in our region direct access to the
financial resources, technology and markets of the developed
world."
</P>
<P>
"It was also globalization that allowed many developing
countries, including those in East Asia, to enjoy decades of
sustained economic growth, rapid industrialization and massive
improvement in their standards of living, health and education,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Touching on the development of the NAM, Jayakumar noted that
its membership has increased from 25 to 114 and its population has
grown from 21 to 50 percent of the world's total since its
establishment in 1961, but its share of the global income has only
grown from 5 to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his belief that the NAM can improve its record in
the new millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
