<HEADLINE> ADB Holds Seminar in Nepal on Consulting Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) is organizing a seminar here in an effort to improve Nepal's
capacity in strengthening implementation performance of
development projects through the efficient use of consulting
services.
</P>
<P>
The bank said Thursday that 38 people from various ministries
of Nepal and 18 ongoing ADB-assisted projects in the country are
attending the seminar to discuss current government and bank
procedures and practices in the use of consultants in development
projects.
</P>
<P>
The three-day seminar which started Wednesday focuses on
identification of major constraints and issues affecting the use
of consulting services and attempt to reconcile the procedures of
the government with the ADB's and coming up with viable solutions,
the bank said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
It noted that while recruitment of consultants for ADB-assisted
projects in Nepal has improved in recent years, delays have still
been experienced by some projects, constituting one of the major
sources of delays in project implementation.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, organized jointly with the Nepali government, will
analyze the problems in further detail and formulate measures to
address them through a participatory approach involving government
officials directly or indirectly associated with implementation of
projects in general and selection of consultants in particular,
the bank added.
</P>
<P>
ADB began operation in Nepal in December 1966 and its
cumulative lending to the country has reached 1.6 billion U.S.
dollars for 92 projects with focus on agriculture and energy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
