<HEADLINE> U.S. Workers Productivity Slows in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. productivity of
nonfarm, nonsupervisory workers, rose at a 0.1 percent annual rate
in the second quarter, the smallest pace in nearly two years, the
Labor Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
That's better than advance estimates, released last month,
which speculated that productivity had actually fallen 0.2 percent
in the second quarter. But it's still the worst showing since the
third quarter of 1996, when productivity was unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The quarterly weakness followed a healthy 3.5 percent increase
in productivity during the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe that productivity has slowed because
employers are hoarding workers, even though they may have less for
them to do.
</P>
<P>
Growth in workers' output dropped sharply in the second
quarter, to a 1.6 percent annual rate from 7 percent during the
first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Unit labor costs, a key measure of inflation pressure,
increased at a 3.9 percent annual rate from April through June.
They had grown at a modest 1.1 percent rate in the first quarter
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Healthy productivity gains have been cited as a key to the
nation's prosperity in the last two years. After a slump during
which productivity grew at only about a 1 percent annual rate from
1974 to 1995, it picked up to a 2.4 percent rate in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
