<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Claims Remain Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September (Xinhua) -- The U.S. unemployment claims
still remained low and the number of first-time applicants for
unemployment benefits rose by 1,000 to a seasonally adjusted
302,000 last week, the Labor Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, a four-week moving average of claims fell to 302,250
from 303,750 for the period ended one week earlier. That's the
lowest level in a year.
</P>
<P>
The financial trouble spreading from Asia has affected the U.S.
exports and as a result, U.S. economic growth slowed to a 1.6
percent annual rate in the second quarter from a robust 5.5
percent growth during the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
But jobs remain plentiful so far. Weekly unemployment claims
have hovered near 300,000 since settling back from this year's
high of 394,000, reached in two weeks during the General Motors
strike in late June and early July.
</P>
<P>
Even with the strike, the nation's unemployment rate in July
remained near a 28-year low, at 4.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
