<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Staff on Crashed Swissair Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- There are more than 10
U.N. staff in the Swissair plane that crashed off Canada
Wednesday, killing all 229 aboard, U.N. sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
No names were immediately released. Officials of the
Geneva-based World Health Organization (WHO) said earlier that the
passengers included Dr. Jonathan Mann, funding director of WHO's
Global Program on AIDS, and his wife.
</P>
<P>
The New York-Geneva route is heavily traveled by U.N. staff and
diplomats flying between U.N. headquarters in New York and the
world body's European office in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The airliner took off from New York's Kennedy airport at 7.53
pm EDT Wednesday. Swissair said the pilot had jettisoned fuel
before the crash.
</P>
<P>
The disaster was the worst in the history of Swiss aviation.
Swissair has one of the world's best safety records, and the crash
is the first disaster to hit it since October 1979 when a
Beijing-bound DC8 carrying 142 people crashed into a wire fence
while landing at Athens airport, killing 14 people.
</P>
<P>
Thursday morning at the headquarters of the United Nations in
New York, there are no flags of the member states flying in front
of the Secretariat building, and the U.N. flag is flying at
half-mast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
