<HEADLINE> Clinton in Omagh to See Bomb Survivors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
arrived in Omagh Thursday afternoon to meet survivors and victims'
relatives of the bomb blast, according to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
In his a few hours trip, he will also lay a wreath to the
victims of the car bombing that killed 28 people and injured 220
others on August 15 in the small town some 110 km west of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Omagh has been struck by almost 30 bombs over the past 30 years
of guerrilla conflict, claiming 150 lives.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived in Northern Ireland Thursday morning for a
one-day trip to the British province to show his support for the
peace process after the deadly bombing in Omagh last month.
</P>
<P>
People of all ages paused Thursday to reflect on the
devastation to the town and the boost given by Clinton's visit,
part of his visit to Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Before he arrived in Omagh, Clinton and British Prime Minister
Tony Blair expressed their sorrow in Belfast over the crash of a
Swissair airliner into the Atlantic, killing all 229 passengers
and crew.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in a speech that "our thoughts and prayers" are
with the victims and their families.
</P>
<P>
"We hope for the best and we are deeply grieved that this has
occurred," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair also showed his grief at the same occasion, saying, "You
have all our thoughts and prayers." 
</P>
</TEXT>
