<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Saddened by Swissair Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Thursday that he was "deeply saddened" by the
deaths of more than 200 victims of the air disaster Wednesday
night near Halifax, Nova Scotia, including a number of members of
the United Nations family.
</P>
<P>
"These include United Nations staff who worked for the welfare
of children, the care of refugees, a cure for HIV/AIDS, and the
protection of the world's intellectual property -- their loss is
felt not only personally but professionally as well," the U.N.
chief said in a statement issued through his spokesman's office
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"My heartfelt sympathy goes out to the families of all the
victims, and in particular to the relatives and friends of those
who lost their lives in the service of the ideals of the United
Nations," Annan said. He is currently in Durban, South Africa, to
attend the Non-aligned Movement summit.
</P>
<P>
Upon the sad news of the air crash, the United Nations flag was
flown at half-mast Thursday morning in New York, the U.N.
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The director-general of the United Nations Office at Geneva,
Vladimir Petrovsky, decided that the U.N. flag would be flown at
half-mast at the Geneva Office Friday, U.N. information service
said.
</P>
<P>
More than 10 staff of the United Nations or its related
agencies were aboard the Swissair plane that crashed off Nova
Scotia, Canada, with no apparent survivors, a U.N. source said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plane carrying 229 passengers and crew members crashed late
Wednesday night off Nova Scotia while on a flight from Kennedy
International Airport in New York to Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The New York-Geneva route is heavily traveled by U.N. staff and
diplomats flying between U.N. headquarters and the world body's
European office in Geneva. 
</P>
</TEXT>
