<HEADLINE> Euro Bank Chief Sees No Serious Impact on Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- President of the European Central
Bank Wim Duisenberg said Thursday that he expected no serious
impact on the overall economic development in Europe from the
Russian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
After meeting German President Roman Herzog in Berlin,
Duisenberg said that the Russian crisis had only evoked relatively
calm reactions from other European countries so far and he
believed that it would remain so in the future.
</P>
<P>
Duisenberg, who formally took office in July this year, also
expressed satisfaction that the planned single European currency,
the euro, had been widely accepted by German citizens despite
their initial scepticism.
</P>
<P>
The euro is due to be launched on January 1, 1999 in 11
European Union countries and will formally become the only legal
tender in those countries up from 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
