<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development is Not Smooth: Chinese Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN (South Africa), September 3 (Xinhua) -- Economic
globalization has posed "serious challenges" to deeloping
countries, Tang Jiaxuan, head of the Chinese delegation to the
Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) summit, said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the summit, the Chinese foreign minister said that
as the trend toward the multi-polarity and globalization has
picked up speed, countries in the world are becoming all the more
inter-dependent.
</P>
<P>
While the developing nations as a whole are gaining strength
and playing a greater role in international affairs, economic
globalization has posed serious challenges for many developing
countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The gap between developed countries and developing ones
continues to widen," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tang told the summit that various destabilizing factors will
linger on while the world situation is moving toward relaxation.
</P>
<P>
He cited these destabilizing factors as stalemated Middle East
peace process, the escalating nuclear arms race in South Asia and
armed conflicts cropping up in certain regions in Africa and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
"All these are a constant warning for us that the road to
development is by no means smooth," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Despite the major changes on the international scene, the NAM
remains "a force not to be ignored on the international arena in
the political, economic and cultural fields", he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister expressed his belief that the
non-aligned countries will face up to the challenges, further
enhance their solidarity, continue to play a constructive role in
safeguarding the interests of developing countries and promoting
the establishment of a just and equitable new international
political and economic order.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
