<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dock Workers' Clashes Leave 50 Injured in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Violent clashes between rival
dock workers on Thursday left some 50 injured and halted the
Chittagong Port operations as a minister went to negotiate a deal
for establishing a private container terminal there.
</P>
<P>
The Chittagong Dock Bandar Sramik Karmachari Parishad (CDBSKP),
a platform of 22 trade unions strongly opposed to a government
decision to allow the construction of a private terminal nearby,
slapped a shutdown on the port in an instant protest, the
Associated Press of Bangladesh reported.
</P>
<P>
The clash occurred at about 10:30 a.m. local time near the
Bandar Bhaban (building) when a procession of CDBSKP staging a
black-flag protest confronted a white-flag procession of
Newmooring Patenga Terminal Implantation Council, a platform of
three trade unions favoring the establishment of the planned
private terminal.
</P>
<P>
Both groups used sticks and bricks in the rioting, which took
place also ahead of the arrival of a mission of the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) for a spot appraisal of its assistance for
the port sector.
</P>
<P>
The rival groups clashed once again when CDBSKP supporters were
holding a rally in front of the Bandar Bhaban at 10:45 a.m. which
lasted 15 minutes. Police fired tear shells and blank shots to
quell the rioters.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also confronted at Nimtala in the port area, this
time with firearms, at about 11:15 a.m. Police pacified the
situation by lobbing tear shells and firing in the air.
</P>
<P>
Ten seriously-wounded workers were admitted to Bandar Hospital
from where four in critical condition were shifted to the
Chittagong Medical College Hospital.
</P>
<P>
The CDBSKP leaders at an impromptu press conference gave an
indefinite strike call in the port and stopped work, resulting in
a deadlock at the seaport, the country's commercial heartland.
</P>
<P>
They said they would not call off the strike until the
government decision on the establishment of the private container
terminal is rescinded.
</P>
<P>
Their demands also included immediate resignation of Deputy
Shipping Minister Saber Hossain, whom they accused of trying to
"sell out the interests of the port," compensation for the wounded
workers and punishment of those involved in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
The deputy shipping minister arrived in Chittagong Wednesday to
hold a meeting with the eight-member ADB mission on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chittagong Port Authority officials were holding a
reconciliation meeting with CDBSKP while tensions mounted in the
port area with a huge contingent of police keeping watch on the
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
