<HEADLINE> Iranian Drivers Freed by Taliban Arrive in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Five Iranian drivers
released by the Islamic Taliban militia arrived here Thursday from
the southern Afghan city of Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian drivers who flew in on a special plane along with a
joint Pak-Iranian delegation Thursday evening were greeted at the
airport by senior officials from Pakistan's Foreign Office and
the Iranian Embassy in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The Pak-Iranian delegation led by Ayaz Wazir, director of
Afghan affairs in the Pakistani Foreign Office, and Abdullahi, a
senior Iranian diplomat in Pakistan, went to Kandahar on the
special plane Thursday morning, a day after the Taliban
authorities announced that they would release the Iranians.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's supreme leader, Mohammad Omar, announced
Wednesday that "as a goodwill gesture," the militia would release
three out of 30 Iranian drivers they arrested last month when they
overran Mazar-e-Sharif, headquarters of the rival Northern
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban claimed that these Iranian drivers were sending
weapons to the pro-Iranian Northern Alliance while the Iranian
government said they were carrying humanitarian aid to northern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Iranian government claimed that its 11 diplomats
in Mazar-e-Sharif, about 300 kilometers north of Kabul, have also
been kidnapped by the Taliban, which denied the accusation.
</P>
