<HEADLINE> Iraqi Kurdish Factions to Discuss Creating Joint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of two rivaling Iraqi
Kurdish factions will meet soon in Washington to discuss creating
a joint administration in northern Iraq, Turkey's Anatolia News
Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) Chairman Massoud Barzani and
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) leader Celal Talabani will
attend the Washington meeting, KDP spokesman Sami Abdurrahman was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the meeting was held in Washington because
"the United States wants to mediate between the two groups".
</P>
<P>
He noted that the basic dispute between the KDP and PUK is the
sharing of the administration. "We wanted the joint administration
in 1992, but the PUK defended the view that the administration has
to be shared equally between the two sides," he said.
</P>
<P>
Barzani, who arrived here Wednesday night for a visit, will
travel to Washington on Saturday after concluding his talks with
Turkish leaders.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Barzani will meet with Turkish parliamentary Speaker
Hikmet Cetin, Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit and Foreign
Minister Ismail Cem to exchange views on the proposed joint
administration and the activities of the outlawed anti-Turkish
Kurdish Workers' Party in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In March, Talabani sent a letter to Massoud seeking a
broad reconciliation in a bid to set up a permanent peace in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Talabani proposed a high-level meeting between
the two factions to sort out their differences.
</P>
<P>
The two groups have fought for control of northern Iraq
after the 1991 Gulf War undermined Baghdad's ability to exert
influence there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
