<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian PM Sad at Swiss Plane Crash Off Canadian Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien expressed Thursday sadness on behalf of the Canadian
people at the news that a Swissair jet had crashed into the ocean
off the coast of Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
The latest report said that 36 bodies have been recovered from
the crash. But there has been no survivors.
</P>
<P>
Swissair also confirmed that there were no survivors from the
crash. All 215 passengers and 14 crew aboard Flight 111 are
believed to have died.
</P>
<P>
The wide-bodied MD-11 jet crashed about 10:30 p.m.local time
(0130 GMT) Wednesday into the ocean 11 kilometers from Peggy's
Cove, a tiny fishing village on the south shore of Canada's Nova
Scotia province.
</P>
<P>
"The families and loved ones of those who have been lost in
this terrible disaster are in all of our thoughts and prayers,"
Chretien said in statement.
</P>
<P>
Chretien said he had written to Swiss President Flavio Cotti
expressing the deepest sympathies of the Canadian people, and
pledging that every resource at Canada's disposal is being devoted
to the recovery effort and the investigation.
</P>
<P>
The three-engine plane, en route from New York to Geneva,
reported smoke in the cockpit after a normal takeoff from the JFK
international airport in New York.
</P>
<P>
The crew decided to turn back to Boston. After being told that
the Halifax airport was closer, the plane flew in the direction of
Halifax, but crashed into the Atlantic about 60 kilometers short
of its target.
</P>
<P>
Military aircraft, coast guard vessels and fishing boats scoured
the crash waters through the night.
</P>
<P>
Yet the inky and rough water made it difficult for rescue teams
to navigate through the debris field, which spread a couple of
kilometers across the sea.
</P>
<P>
As dawn broke on the southwest coast of Nova Scotia, a
shoreline search got under way.
</P>
<P>
"At this point, our main focus is on recovering the bodies,"
said Roy Bears of Canada's Transportation Safety Board, one of the
lead agencies in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Divers will be moved in to try to recover flight recorders from
the plane, the reports said. The water in the area is about 50
meters deep.
</P>
<P>
Canadian police appealed to the public Thursday to turn in any
debris from the crash, which might wash up the shore.
</P>
<P>
The weather there was reported to be overcast, with a light
sprinkle of rain.
</P>
<P>
Boeing, the maker of the jet, was sending a team of people to
Nova Scotia to help in the investigation of the crash.
</P>
<P>
The United States also sent a team of investigators to the
crash site, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
