<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Inspects Flood-Ravaged Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGDE (Hunan Province), September 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese
President Jiang Zemin today urged continued vigilance along the
Yangtze River and pledged that the government will provide for the
daily needs of flood victims.
</P>
<P>
The president arrived in Hunan Province this morning to begin a
fact-finding tour of flood-ravaged areas. Local officials briefed
the president on flood control operations and Jiang said that
receding flood waters along the Yangtze do not indicate the end of
this year's flood season. He noted that water levels in many
sections remain above danger levels.
</P>
<P>
He called for continued vigilance and urged people engaged in
the flood control effort to take effective measures to ensure the
safety of levees and strive for ultimate success.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who is also general secretary of the Chinese Communist
Party Central Committee and chairman of the Central Military
Commission, said efforts must be made to guarantee the basic daily
needs of people in flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
"We must ensure victims have adequate food, clean drinking
water and clothing. They must have adequate shelter and access to
immediate medical care," Jiang told local officials, adding that
local governments should make arrangements to help victims cope
with the coming winter.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the great importance in stablizing public order
and maintaining security in disaster areas. He said efforts must
be made to ensure that schools open on schedule and noted that
universities should provide assistance and provide financial aid
to students from disaster areas if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also discussed reconstruction and stressed that special
attention should be attached to reducing burdens on farmers.
</P>
<P>
Braving heavy wind and rain, President Jiang Zemin went to
flood-fighting scenes in Anxiang County, Hunan Province this
afternoon and met with armymen and civilians fighting floods on
the levees.
</P>
<P>
Jiang shook hands with soldiers on the levee that had been
breached in late July but were patched up after 11 day-and-night
efforts. He thanked the soldiers for their contributions to
fighting the floods and protecting people's lives and properties.
</P>
<P>
He also met with Wang Chixiang, wife of a local environmental
protection official who died on August 27 while fighting floods
on the levee.
</P>
<P>
Jiang later went to visit evacuation camps scattered on the
70-kilometer levee, where about 100,000 people are living in tents
or makeshift shelters.
</P>
<P>
He stopped to visit a temporary primary school where some 160
children were having classes in eight tents. The president asked
the students to treasure their chances to study.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also visited medical workers on the levee where they were
offering medical service to local patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
