<HEADLINE> U.N. Flag Flown at Half-Mast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
headquarters in New York Thursday morning flew the U.N. flag at
half-mast and took down all national flags of 185 member countries
in a sign of mourning over the deaths in the Swissair crash.
</P>
<P>
"The decision was made mid-morning," U.N. Spokesman Fred
Eckhard told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The 229 air crash victims included five U.N. staff members who
worked for the U.N. Children's Fund, the Intellectual Property
Organization and the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees and
Jonathan Mann, a famous American expert on AIDS, who worked with
the World Health Organization, he said.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Petrovsky, director-general of the U.N. office in
Geneva, said that the U.N. flag would be flown at half-mast Friday
at the Geneva Office.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan gave a press conference in
South Africa Thursday morning (local time) to voice his sad
feeling over the air disaster, the spokesman said, adding that
Annan "was deeply moved as he knew some of the victims
personally." The U.N. chief is currently in Durban, South Africa,
to attend the Non-aligned Movement summit.
</P>
<P>
A Swissair plane with 229 people aboard Wednesday night crashed
off Nova Scotia, Canada, on a flight from New York to Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. headquarters is following an investigation currently
being carried out by Canada and Switzerland, the spokesman added.
</P>
</TEXT>
