<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Bankruptcy Wave Calms Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The steady increases in corporate
bankruptcies registered since 1991 in Germany are coming to a stop
gradually thanks to an improving economy, the German Statistics
Office said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bankruptcies, which still rose at a record-setting pace
early this year, now concentrated more on smaller companies
instead of the big ones, a signal for a trend reversal as past
experience showed, said President of the Statistics Office Johann
Hahlen in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The office's latest data showed that a total of 13,998
companies declared bankruptcy in the first half of this year, up
only 3.1 percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
By comparison, Germany's bankruptcy total increased by 7.6
percent in 1997 and 14.3 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
For the month of June alone, Germany registered only 2,180
corporate bankruptcies, down 16.7 percent from a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
