<HEADLINE> Greece Pledges to Stick to Target of Joining EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Despite an economic crisis
hitting the world markets, Greece vowed Thursday that it would
stick to its target of joining the European Economic and Monetary
Union (EMU) by January 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a cabinet meeting, Greek government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas said that the government would keep, as
this year, the same targets in its economic policy for 1999.
</P>
<P>
This was the only right recipe, he said, adding that this
year's economic policy aimed at cutting inflation and deficits,
shrinking the public sector and making structural changes to the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the Greek government, which was
concerned at the financial fallout from Russia's crisis, could not
rule out the possibility of renewed turmoil, but believed any
fresh eruption could, to some extent, be controlled.
</P>
<P>
Greece has said that the drachmas' entry into the exchange rate
mechanism has strengthened the country's economic credibility and
is working as a shied against the current crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
