<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Recover Amidst Worries Over Russian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) - Oil prices seem to be staging a
recovery as potential long disruptions to Russian supplies began
to unnerve the markets.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Brent burst above 13 U.S. dollars a barrel
Thursday for the first time in a month, trading at 13.01 U.S.
dollars at one time in the afternoon, up 55 cents over the day.
</P>
<P>
The rebound made some inroads into this year's price losses,
which have dragged Brent values a third below last year's average
of 19.30 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A global stock glut built up early this year as Asian demand
fell away has been stifling any upturn, despite some 3 million
barrels per day of producer cuts aimed at rebalancing the market.
</P>
<P>
But prices have at last got a fillip from the threat that
Russia's financial crisis could seize up its 2.5 million bpd oil
export system, oil market analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Russian crude exports from its main Black Sea and Baltic
outlets have suffered severe cuts since August 28 as the chaos
among Russia's banks prevents lifters from getting hold of the
money to pay necessary customs dues, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
While the odd crude cargo is now loading, traders fear that the
problems could well persist given the scale of Russia's economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
Russia is also a key supplier of oil products such as gas oil
and fuel oil to Europe through the same outlets, although so far
product liftings have not been hard hit.
</P>
<P>
Prolonged problems with Nigerian supply are further draining
supplies to Europe.
</P>
<P>
Royal Dutch/Shell has had to stop some 600,000 bpd of export
from the West African state for around two weeks on technical
problems and pipeline sabotage by disaffected local communities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
