<HEADLINE> Clinton Comforts Survivors of Omagh Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Thursday met and comforted about 500 survivors of the car bomb and
relatives of the victims at a leisure center in Omagh, 110 km west
of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by First Lady Hillary, and British Prime Minister
Tony Blair and his wife Cherie, Clinton said, "To all of you, we
thank you for standing up in the face of such a soul-searing loss,
and restating your determination to walk the road of peace."
</P>
<P>
Twenty-eight died and 220 were injured in the car bomb blast at
a shopping center in Omagh on August 15, the bloodiest day in
almost 30 years of Northern Irish strife.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who arrived earlier in the day in Northern Ireland to
show his support to the peace process, said he had come to Omagh
to support "your determined refusal to let a cowardly crime rob
you of the future you have chosen," according to a BBC report from
Omagh.
</P>
<P>
He also said it was "high time to stop yesterday's nightmares
from killing tomorrow's dreams."
</P>
<P>
"What happened here on August 15 was so incredibly
unreasonable, so shocking to the conscience of every decent person
in this land, that it has perversely had exactly the reverse
impact that the people who perpetrated this act intended.... It
galvanized, strengthened and humanized the impulse to peace,"
Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
