<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Russian Official Warns of Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A ranking Russian official said
Thursday that the current financial crisis may cause serious food
shortages in the country.
</P>
<P>
Andrei Kushnerenko, deputy head of the Ministry for Foreign
Economic Relations and Trade, said foreign firms are stopping
commodity shipments to Russia because they do not trust Russian
banks, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, higher customs payments which resulted in the sharp
devaluation of the ruble have left most importers unable to pay
the tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Russia set the official exchange rate for
Friday at 13.4608 rubles to the U.S. dollar, a drop of some 113.7
percent as compared to the rate half a month ago.
</P>
<P>
Kushnerenko called for radical measures to adjust the country's
customs tariffs policy.
</P>
<P>
As a provisional measure, Kushnerenko said, the government
should reduce customs import tariffs on raw materials for the
Russian food industry.
</P>
<P>
Russian food enterprises buy 60-65 percent of their raw
materials from abroad. The percentage for Moscow perches at 85-90
percent.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if the financial crisis persists and the customs
tariffs policy is not changed, import of Western foodstuffs into
Russia may stop completely.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Viktor Khlystun, director of the
Russian Institute of Agrarian Market Studies, said the financial
crisis will not make Russians starve, but food shortages are
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
Khlystun, a former agriculture and food minister, told Interfax
that shortages of vegetable oil and meat products may be
especially acute.
</P>
<P>
Many Russian consumers may no longer be able to afford imported
vegetable oil as prices, which already shot up on the world
market, rise even higher in the wake of the weak ruble, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0031 </DOCNO>
