<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Spends Billions to Defend Currency in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Canada spent a
total of 5.824 billion U.S. dollars in August to prop up the
Canadian dollar in August, the Finance Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Official government operations decreased reserves by 5,824
million U.S. dollars," the department said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank intervened actively during August "to promote
orderly markets for the Canadian dollar due to turbulence in
international financial markets and downward pressure on the
currency," it said.
</P>
<P>
Canada's official international reserves decreased by an amount
equivalent to 4.555 billion U.S. dollars during August to 17.965
billion dollars in August.
</P>
<P>
The reserves are made up of 11.903 billion U.S. dollars, 2.969
billion dollars in other currencies, 131 million dollars in gold,
1.047 billion dollars in special drawing rights and 1.915 in
reserve position in the International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
