<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban, Iran to Try to Find Missing Iranians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Islamic
Taliban militia and Iran agreed on Thursday to form a joint
investigating team to probe into the whereabouts of the 11 missing
Iranian diplomats in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, five Iranians released by the Taliban arrived here
along with a Pakistani-Iranian joint delegation from the southern
Afghan city of Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
Three of the five were among the 30 Iranian drivers arrested by
the Taliban when the latter overran Mazar-e-Sharif, headquarters
of the pro-Iranian Northern Alliance, in early August. The other
two Iranians were taken by the hard-line militia in Afghanistan
last year.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good step, but it is not enough, they should go
forward," Abdullahi, Iran's deputy consul in Peshawar, who led the
delegation to the Taliban's stronghold to fetch the freed
Iranians, told reporters at the airport.
</P>
<P>
He said the Taliban have promised to give a final statement to
clarify all the earlier controversial ones concerning the 11
Iranian diplomats who have been missing since the Taliban's
capture of Mazar-e-Sharif, about 300 kilometers north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
"In case they are unable to give the final results, a joint
delegation from the Taliban and Iran, with the participation of
the Pakistani brothers, will go to Mazar-e-Sharif to see what
happened to them," Abdullahi said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz Khan, Pakistan's ambassador to Afghanistan, also termed
the release of the five Iranians by the Taliban as a "good
beginning," saying this will help ease the tension between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's envoy in Pakistan, Maulvi Saeed-ur-Rahman,
expressed the hope that this "goodwill gesture" taken by the
Taliban would help the militia and Iran to start negotiations on
the pending issues between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
He said the Taliban government wants to have good relations
with all the neighboring countries but it will not accept any
interference in Afghanistan's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban authorities have claimed that the arrested Iranian
drivers were involved in sending weapons to the Northern Alliance
while the Iranian government stated that they were carrying
humanitarian aid. Meanwhile, the Taliban have said they had no
knowledge of the 11 missing Iranian diplomats, but Iran accused
the militia of kidnapping them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
