<HEADLINE> Indian Armed Forces to Increase Dependency in IT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indian armed forces
would increasingly depend on information technology (IT) with the
information war heralding a new revolution in military affairs,
Indian Defense Minister George Fernandes said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating a conference and exhibition on "Information
Technology in Indian Army," the minister disclosed that his
ministry had established six joint task forces including one on IT
between Defense Services and Confederation of Indian Industry.
</P>
<P>
The Indian services would be a major contributor toward
providing connectivity to civilians in remote areas as part of the
decade-long National Information Technology Vision Program
(1998-2008), Fernandes said.
</P>
<P>
He said the armed forces were committed to establishing centers
of excellence with core competency in many security-related areas
of information technology.
</P>
<P>
As part of the national agenda of the Indian government led by
the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) to make India an IT superpower by
2008, the government has approved a 108-point action plan prepared
by a task force dealing with software, hardware and human resource
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
