<HEADLINE> WB to Assess Aid Needs of Bangladesh Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) --The World Bank (WB) will make
fresh aid commitments for post-flood rehabilitation in Bangladesh
only after the assessment of requirements, the Associated Press of
Bangladesh (APB) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We'll assess with the (Bangladeshi) government what the needs
are (for the rehabilitation programs)," Pierre Landell-Mills, the
bank's country director, was quoted as saying in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
Like previous years, the bank would extend assistance to
Bangladesh to help it heal the damage caused by this year's
floods, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bank has already written to the Bangladeshi government
asking for an outline where the donor agency could extend its
assistance for post-flood rehabilitation works, he added.
</P>
<P>
He further said an assessment of the requirements of aid is
needed for the bank to make any commitment because it cannot
specify any amount without knowing the needs.
</P>
<P>
He however suggested that the government use for the purpose
part of the funds approved by the bank for at least three projects
involving over 650 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The level of the bank's lending (to Bangladesh) has recently
been raised to 600 million-650 million dollars from the earlier
400 million-540 million dollars, showing nearly a 50-percent rise,
he stated. He added that the raise was justified considering the
size of the country's population, level of poverty and its
performance which is "always better than other countries."
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government has appealed to donor countries and
international agencies for assistance to flood victims since the
nearly two-month-long severe flood has caused enormous losses to
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
