<HEADLINE> S. Africa's National Party Losing Ground: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- With the 1999 general
election less than a year away, the voter support for the
National Party (NP), South Africa's biggest opposition party, has
dropped below the psychological level of 10 percent, an opinion
poll showed.
</P>
<P>
The party had nine percent support as in July this year, down
from 10 percent in May and 12 percent in last November, Markinor,
a major independent research company in South Africa, said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The NP, the former ruling party in the apartheid era, won 20
percent of the votes in the country's first democratic election
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Markinor's latest survey showed the ruling African National
Congress (ANC) has increased its support to 57 percent in July
from 54 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The party won 63 percent of the votes in the 1994 election.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Democratic Party, another white-based
opposition party, continued to gain ground, with six percent
support registered in July, up from five percent in May and three
percent in last November.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by secret ballot among 3,499 people,
showed that undecided voters accounted for 13 percent of the
respondents.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the figures, the organization predicted the
political landscape would not change dramatically over the next
few months.
</P>
<P>
It said the ANC stood to re-affirm its position at around 60
percent in the next election, and the real battle lay between the
larger opposition parties running for the second place.
</P>
<P>
With its support continuing to fall and voters' confidence
shaken, the NP leadership could be expected to resort to "rather
desperate measures", such as a return to the government of
national unity, Markinor said.
</P>
<P>
The NP's popularity has been waning since its former leader F
W de Klerk decided to withdrew from the national government in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Refugees Swarm into Tanzania from Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of refugees
flowing into Tanzania from the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
has surpassed 2,400 since the outbreak of war in the country on
August 2, a United Nations refugee agency official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vincent Parker, senior external relations officer of the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), said in
Dar es Salaam that 379 Congolese refugees arrived in Tanzania
Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Among the new arrivals, 174 were adults and 205 were children,
he said, adding that they came to the Kigoma Region in west
Tanzania by boat from a village called Mboko in DRC's Fizi zone.
</P>
<P>
"The group reported that soldiers had allowed them to cross
into Tanzania," Parker said. "It is therefore expected that more
refugees would arrive from the Fizi zone."
</P>
<P>
The officer said that they have set aside two camps for
refugees, Nyarugusu and Lufugu, which have a total capacity to
accommodate 50,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
"For the time being we do not have any problems concerning
food, treatment, shelter and water," he said.
</P>
<P>
The refugees crossed Lake Tanganyika by boat into Kigoma after
Tutsi-led rebels took up arms in the east of DRC to topple the
government of President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, UNHCR officials said the influx of refugees is
manageable, as they are capable of handling even 1,000 new
arrivals a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Publishes Guidelines to Curb Use of Antibiotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The British government Thursday
published new guidelines on the prescribing of antibiotics amid
fears of the emergence of drug-resistant "superbugs."
</P>
<P>
Doctors should not prescribe antibiotics for conditions caused
by viruses such as coughs, colds and sore throats, the Standing
Medical Advisory Committee of the Department of Health said in its
report, The Path of Least Resistance.
</P>
<P>
Other recommendations include a national education campaign to
explain to patients that they should not expect antibiotics when
they go to their doctors, and healthy women with uncomplicated
cystitis should only be prescribed antibiotics for three days.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines were issued ahead of a meeting of chief medical
officers from European Union nations next week in Copenhagen to
devise strategies to control the spread of antibiotic resistant
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
The British government is also trying to use the
recommendations for a national framework on antibiotic use, to be
announced later this year.
</P>
<P>
Antibiotics have revolutionized medical care in the 20th
century, but in recent years the drug-resistant "superbugs" have
been winning the battle against the medical profession.
</P>
<P>
"In the closing years of the century, there is an uneasy sense
that micro-organisms are `getting ahead' and that therapeutic
options are narrowing," The Path of Least Resistance report said.
</P>
<P>
The Public Laboratory in North London has collected figures
showing that the number of people with drug resistant infections
in Britain has quadrupled over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Researchers in Japan have found that a strain of the common
bacterial infection staphylococus aureus did not respond to
vancomycin, one of the most powerful antibiotics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Opposes Unilateral Intervention in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni Thursday told the 12th Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) summit
that Uganda does not accept unilateral military intervention by
individual countries or sectional intervention by groups of
countries in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement when addressing the plenary session
at the NAM summit Thursday morning in Durban, South Africa, a
press release from the President's Office said.
</P>
<P>
NAM has always opposed the presence of foreign troops in
foreign lands, he said, because it always distorts the internal
politics of that country in such a way that the political
questions are not addressed.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Museveni asserted, if foreign army intervenes in
any country, it should be under the very clear supervision of the
United Nations or of recognized regional bodies.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan president condemned the intervention of foreign
troops on the side of a government which is not elected by
popular mandate and urged the countries in the region to discuss
the deepening crisis in the DRC at appropriate regional fora as
they have already started doing.
</P>
<P>
He confessed that Uganda has had troops in eastern DRC for one
year following an understanding with President Laurent Kabila's
government in order to fight barbaric terrorists operating from
that area since the days of late dictator Sese Seko Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
Museveni proposed that the presence of those troops be
reviewed by mutual discussions especially if alternative
arrangements are made for the security of all affected by the
terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
He pledged full support for the initiative raised by South
African President Nelson Mandela on seeking a political
resolution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been accused by Kabila of fomenting the month-long
Tutsi rebellion and of sending troops to support the rebels, a
charge Kampala quickly denied.
</P>
<P>
With the military intervention in the DRC crisis by Zimbabwe,
Angola and Namibia in mid-August, the war began to turn against
the rebels who had advanced to the suburbs of capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Uganda said that it would send troops to the DRC if
the conflict there continues to regionalize and its national
security is under threat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM to Visit Jordan, Israel and Palestine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz is to visit Jordan, Israel and Palestine starting on Sunday
in a bid to play a role in the peace process, Turkish Foreign
Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that bilateral relations, regional and
international issues would be discussed during Yilmaz's visit.
</P>
<P>
It added that several agreements would be signed with an aim to
enhance Turkey's cooperation in various fields with the three
sides.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day visit, Yilmaz is expected to meet with
Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Jordan have maintained closer ties with Ankara, but
the PNA is critical of the rapid expansion of the Turkish-Israeli
military ties.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel began their military cooperation since early
1996 after they signed a deal under which Turkey allowed Israeli
fighter pilots to train in its air space.
</P>
<P>
The past two years witnessed frequent exchanges of visits by
senior military officials between the two countries. The
Turkish-Israeli military cooperation has sparked widespread
protests from the Arab world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
