<HEADLINE> Syria Reopens Trade Center in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 3 (Xinhua) -- In another step toward
restoring its ties with Iraq, Syria Thursday reopened its trade
center in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh and Director-General
of the Syrian head of Free Trade Zones Khalid Raad inaugurated the
center, where samples of Syrian-made medicine, foodstuff and
clothes were displayed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, the Iraqi minister said the reopening of
the Syrian trade center in Baghdad would make contributions to the
expansion of the bilateral trade ties.
</P>
<P>
He said the trade volume between the two countries has amounted
to about 150 million U.S. dollars since last year, emphasizing
Iraq's wishes to broaden trade cooperation with Syria in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Raad said the reopening of the trade center was a step to
further strengthen the bilateral relations and that it could serve
as a window of Syrian goods for the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian official paid tribute to the efforts exerted by the
two sides to speed up the reopening of the center and an Iraqi one
in Syria's capital Damascus.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic relations between Iraq and Syria were severed in
1980 due to Syria's support for Iran during the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq
War.
</P>
<P>
But the bilateral ties in the trade and economic fields have
been improving recently. Baghdad and Damascus have already agreed
to reopen oil pipelines linking Iraq's northern oil-fields and
Syria's Mediterranean ports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
