<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One in Five Banking Personnel May Lose Job in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Up to 15-20 percent of workers
in the Russian banking sector will lose their jobs in the wake of
the financial crisis, an industry official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This is rooted in the government's erroneous moves, not in
poor bank management," Sergei Yegorov, Association of Russian
Banks President Sergei Yegorov said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the layoffs to the banking crisis caused by the
collapse of the state securities market.
</P>
<P>
Interfax said the future of the banks and the number of workers
to be dismissed will depend on the degree of the population's
trust in commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, investors have closed about 15 percent of their
deposits with commercial banks, Interfax reported, quoting
prominent bankers.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, leading employment agencies estimate that between
40,000 and 100,000 employees of banks and financial and investment
companies will lose their jobs in the next two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
