<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Refugees Swarm into Tanzania from Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of refugees
flowing into Tanzania from the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
has surpassed 2,400 since the outbreak of war in the country on
August 2, a United Nations refugee agency official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vincent Parker, senior external relations officer of the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), said in
Dar es Salaam that 379 Congolese refugees arrived in Tanzania
Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Among the new arrivals, 174 were adults and 205 were children,
he said, adding that they came to the Kigoma Region in west
Tanzania by boat from a village called Mboko in DRC's Fizi zone.
</P>
<P>
"The group reported that soldiers had allowed them to cross
into Tanzania," Parker said. "It is therefore expected that more
refugees would arrive from the Fizi zone."
</P>
<P>
The officer said that they have set aside two camps for
refugees, Nyarugusu and Lufugu, which have a total capacity to
accommodate 50,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
"For the time being we do not have any problems concerning
food, treatment, shelter and water," he said.
</P>
<P>
The refugees crossed Lake Tanganyika by boat into Kigoma after
Tutsi-led rebels took up arms in the east of DRC to topple the
government of President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, UNHCR officials said the influx of refugees is
manageable, as they are capable of handling even 1,000 new
arrivals a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
