<HEADLINE> Iraqi Trade Ties With Neighbors Improving: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed
Mehdi Saleh said Thursday that Iraq's trade relations with
neighboring states have "progressively developed."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted Saleh as saying that many Arab
states have shown willingness to reopen trade centers in Iraq. The
minister made the remarks after attending the inauguration of the
Syrian trade center in Baghdad Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Iraq and Saudi Arabia, one of its major
rivals, are holding negotiations on exporting Saudi foodstuffs to
Iraq within the framework of the U.N. oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
But Saleh accused the U.S. and Britain of delaying approval of
contracts that Iraq has signed with foreign companies under the
oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed sanctions on Iraq after its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990, but it signed the oil-for-food deal
with Iraq in December 1996 to allow it to export 2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil every six months to buy food, medicine
and other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
The ceiling was raised to 5.2 billion U.S. dollars in the fourth
phase, which began on June 3 this year.
</P>
<P>
Saleh noted that the value of contracts Iraq have signed so far
in the fourth phase has exceeded the allocations set aside from
the proceeds of oil sales due to the sagging oil prices.
</P>
<P>
But he said Iraq would commit itself to the implementation of a
decision made by the Arab Economic and Social Unity Council to cut
10 percent of tariffs on Iraqi commodities imported from Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that Iraq would attend the meeting of the council
to be held in Cairo next week to discuss means of upholding the
decision. It also hopes to use the chance to further enhance its
ties with other Arab countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
