<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's National Party Losing Ground: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- With the 1999 general
election less than a year away, the voter support for the
National Party (NP), South Africa's biggest opposition party, has
dropped below the psychological level of 10 percent, an opinion
poll showed.
</P>
<P>
The party had nine percent support as in July this year, down
from 10 percent in May and 12 percent in last November, Markinor,
a major independent research company in South Africa, said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The NP, the former ruling party in the apartheid era, won 20
percent of the votes in the country's first democratic election
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Markinor's latest survey showed the ruling African National
Congress (ANC) has increased its support to 57 percent in July
from 54 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The party won 63 percent of the votes in the 1994 election.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Democratic Party, another white-based
opposition party, continued to gain ground, with six percent
support registered in July, up from five percent in May and three
percent in last November.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by secret ballot among 3,499 people,
showed that undecided voters accounted for 13 percent of the
respondents.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the figures, the organization predicted the
political landscape would not change dramatically over the next
few months.
</P>
<P>
It said the ANC stood to re-affirm its position at around 60
percent in the next election, and the real battle lay between the
larger opposition parties running for the second place.
</P>
<P>
With its support continuing to fall and voters' confidence
shaken, the NP leadership could be expected to resort to "rather
desperate measures", such as a return to the government of
national unity, Markinor said.
</P>
<P>
The NP's popularity has been waning since its former leader F
W de Klerk decided to withdrew from the national government in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
