<HEADLINE> Museveni Outlines Uganda's Development at NAM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has outlined his country's development at the 12th
summit of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the President's Office said Thursday that
Museveni enumerated the four main objectives of Uganda's
development strategy: the development of human resources through
education for all, the development of infrastructure,
industrialization and development of the service sector as well
as the modernization of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The president told the summit that Uganda has made modest
gains in the last 12 years. Its gross domestic product (GDP),
industrial and agricultural sectors have grown 6.5, 15 and 6.3
percents per annum respectively.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate is maintained between three to five percent
while the primary school enrollment has been doubled, he added.
</P>
<P>
The fundamental change has been to accept private sector-led
growth which has moved the east African country away from a
command economy.
</P>
<P>
Judging by Uganda's development, Africa is capable of waking
up, he said, hoping the non-African members of the 113-member NAM
to be fully confident that they have reliable partners in Africa
in their quest for development and progress.
</P>
<P>
The NAM summit, which opened Wednesday, is expected to address
disarmament, development and regional conflicts. 
</P>
