<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Hurricane Earl landed the
southern United States early Thursday, lashing the Florida
Panhandle with 130 kph winds and torrential rain, killing at least
one person and leading three more missing.
</P>
<P>
A tornado ahead of the main part of the storm damaged homes and
killed one person on St. Helena Island near the southern tip of
South Carolina. One person was missing there, the Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
Also missing were two fishermen off Panama City when their
boats capsized Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Trees were knocked down and parts of U.S. Highway 98 washed
away near the Florida coast. Tornadoes struck six Florida
counties, damaging some homes, but no serious injuries were
reported.
</P>
<P>
All 1,500 homes on the St. George Island and 20,000 customers
across the Panhandle lost power.
</P>
<P>
The storm was downgraded to a tropical storm late Thursday
morning, but flooding was threatened to the Southeast of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
A flood watch covered a wide area from Tallahassee east to
Jacksonville and south to Tampa Bay, as well as parts of Georgia
and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of tourists fled the Gulf Coast before Earl moved
ashore. 
</P>
