<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Launch 2nd Phase of Forestation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia announced
Thursday that the second phase of the project on the sustainable
preservation and development of plant resources will be
undertaken in 1998/99 at a cost of 2.1 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The manager of the forest resources registration and strategic
planning project under the agriculture ministry, Sultan Tilimo,
told reporters here that the project covers 700,000 square
kilometers, or 62 percent of the total area of the country.
</P>
<P>
Sultan recalled that survey and strategy formulation were
carried out during the first phase of the project between 1991
and 1994 over an area covering 300,000 square kilometers in the
southern people's region, Gambella Region, 80 percent of Oromiya
Region and 30 percent of Benishangul Region.
</P>
<P>
The problem of fuel wood is growing to be critical unless
alternative measures are sought, the manager said, adding that
the project will also devise a strategy for the development of
the agricultural sector which is the mainstay of more than 80
percent of the people in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian government will allocate a total of 6.7 million
U.S. Dollars for the execution of the whole project which is
expected to be completed in 2002, according to Sultan.
</P>
<P>
Forestry coverage rate in Ethiopia is only three percent. The
nation loses 1.9 billion tons of soil to erosion every year.
</P>
