<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-03 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denktash Urges Cyprus to Reconsider Confederation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash warned Thursday of eternal division of Cyprus if the
Cypriot government does not accept his proposal for creating a
confederation in the divided island.
</P>
<P>
"If they (the Greek Cypriots) do not accept confederation, the
two states on the island will go their own way," Denktash said in
a meeting with chief of the security forces of the Turkish
Cypriots Ali Nihat Ozeyranli, Turkey's Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Cypriot government to reconsider its position
on his proposal, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Denktash proposed on Monday setting up a confederation of
"equal and sovereign states" of the Greek Cypriots and Turkish
Cypriots as way to end the 24-year-old division of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He called his proposal as "a final effort" to achieve a
"mutually acceptable" and lasting solution to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has flatly rejected the proposal,
dismissing it as an attempt to render an independent sovereign
state into two protectorates.
</P>
<P>
But Denktash insisted that his proposal is the "most realistic"
for reviving the negotiations between the two communities.
</P>
<P>
The bi-communal peace process came to a halt in the summer last
year when Denktash walked out of the talks with Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides to protest the European Union (EU) decision to
start entry negotiations with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Denktash said he would not return to the negotiations unless
his breakaway Turkish Cypriot regime in northern Cyprus is
internationally recognized and Cyprus stops the entry talks with
the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Only Turkey has recognized the breakaway "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus," which was declared by Turkish Cypriots in 1983
against the internationally acknowledged Republic of
Cyprus. Turkey is now stationing 35,000-strong troops in the
norther allegedly to protect the Turkish Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
