<HEADLINE> Clinton, Blair Voice Sorrow over Swiss Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and
British Prime Minister Tony Blair Thursday expressed their sorrow
over the crash of a Swissair airliner which killed all 229
passengers and crew on board.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who is on a one-day visit to Britain's Northern
Ireland region, told a gathering in Belfast: "our thoughts and
prayers" are with the victims and their families.
</P>
<P>
"Canadians are conducting an extensive search operation. We
hope for the best and we are deeply grieved that this has
occurred," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Prime Minister Blair said: "You (victims
and family members) have all our thoughts and prayers."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that six British citizens were among the 215
passengers on the airliner which crashed into the sea of Nova
Scotia, Canada. 
