<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breakaway UNITA Faction Sets Up Renovation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Some members of the opposition
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) who broke
up with their leader Jonas Savimbi set up the Committee for UNITA
Renovation here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the breakaway UNITA faction is to give up war,
keep onto the track of the peace process and remove Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos who is attending the
12th Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) summit in Durban, South Africa,
congratulated the UNITA defectors on the establishment of the
Committee for UNITA Renovation, saying that his government will
only engage the committee in the pursuit of a lasting peace in
the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
A group of UNITA members who hold posts in the government, led
by Minister of Hotel and Tourism Jorge Valentim, released a
declaration calling on the patriotic UNITA members to choose the
right way of national reconciliation, to abandon Savimbi's
leadership which insists on fighting and to elect new leaders.
</P>
<P>
The declaration has been echoed in parts of the country. In
northern Uige Province, some UNITA members holding posts in the
provincial government wrote a letter Thursday to Governor
Cananito Alexandre, demonstrating their support for national
unity, the government of reconciliation and democracy.
</P>
<P>
In central Huambo Province, UNITA officials in the provincial
government also dismissed the war policy of Savimbi and declared
severance with him and his leading organ.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan peace process is facing the most serious crisis in
four years because the UNITA did not fully follow the 1994 Lusaka
Peace Accord. The opposition movement refused to disband all of
its troops and turn the cities and towns formerly controlled by
it over to the government.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government Monday decided to suspend the UNITA
members in the national congress and the government of national
unity and reconciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
