<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Issues Stamps on Return of Axum Obelisk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Postal
Service Thursday issued a set of three memorial stamps on the
return of the Axum Obelisk from Italy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching ceremony, Minister of Information
and Culture Woldemechael Chemu said that the governments of
Ethiopia and Italy have been working closely to make sure that
the Axum Obelisk returns to its rightful owner, Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Final preparations are being made to ensure the safe return
from Italy to Ethiopia of the obelisk, Woldemechael said, adding
that the obelisk will be dismantled, packed and transported to
Ethiopia in a few months time.
</P>
<P>
He said that an international relic study and research center
entrusted with the task of dismantling and shipping the obelisk
back to Ethiopia is making the necessary studies.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian people are ready to warmly welcome their obelisk
back home, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The Axum Obelisk which now stands in front of the United
Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) headquarters in
Rome, Italy, is one of the three obelisks erected in the ancient
town of Axum of northern Ethiopia centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
The obelisk looted from Axum Town in 1937 by the invading
Italian forces under the direct command of Mussolini is 24 meters
tall and weighs 144 tons.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Ethiopia and Italy reached an agreement for
the return of the Axum Obelisk in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The largest of the three obelisks which has fallen measures 34
meters in length and weighs 520 tons. The other which is 23
meters high is still standing in Axum.
</P>
<P>
The monolithic obelisks are cut out of granite which comes
from a high rocky stretch of land known as Gebedera, five
kilometers away from Axum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
