<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Foreigners Killed on S. African Train </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Three foreigners, two
from Senegal and one from Mozambique, were killed on a train near
Pretoria Thursday after a mob accused them of stealing jobs from
South Africans, South African media reported.
</P>
<P>
Two of the victims were electrocuted by overhead wires when
they tried to escape the mob by climbing on to the train roof. A
third man fell or was thrown out of the window and run over by an
oncoming train, South African Press Association (SAPA) said.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred at 4.30 p.m. (1430 GMT) on a train
traveling from Pretoria to Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
There have been no arrests.
</P>
<P>
"People on the train are reluctant to come forward with
evidence, and the information we have at present is vague,"
police spokesman George Francis was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said two placards were found near the train after the
incident. They read "Down with foreigners, they are taking our
jobs" and "We will take the law into our hands."
</P>
<P>
Pretoria Metrorail spokeswoman Margaret Dingalo said that a
number of people who participated in a protest march to the
offices of the departments of labor and home affairs in Pretoria
earlier in the day to demand job creation were on the train.
</P>
<P>
The marchers were members of an organization called Unemployed
Masses of South Africa, which claims to represent 32,000 jobless
people.
</P>
<P>
Trains on the central line between Pretoria and Johannesburg
came to a standstill during the peak commuter hour while police
removed the bodies.
</P>
<P>
Trains were delayed for 2.5 hours and about 30 trains were
affected, said Dingalo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
