<HEADLINE> UNICEF Chief Mourns Staff Deaths in Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Children's
Fund (UNICEF) on Thursday voiced deep sadness at the death of its
two members and a former member in the air crash on Thursday,
saying "UNICEF and the UN as a whole has suffered a grievous
loss."
</P>
<P>
Carol Bellamy, executive director of the New York-based
UNICEF, said in a statement that "Our hearts and prayers go out
to the families and colleagues of all who were on the
(ill-fated) flight. UNICEF and the UN as a whole has suffered a
grievous loss."
</P>
<P>
Three members of the UNICEF were among 229 people aboard a
Swissair plane before it crashed off Nova Scotia, Canada,
Wednesday night (Local time). No survivors have been found so far
despite pains-taking efforts by rescue workers.
</P>
<P>
The victims from the U.N. agency were Yves de Roussan (Canada),
a staff member of the UNICEF, Ms. Ingrid Acevedo, a staff member
of the U.S. Committee for UNICEF, and a former UNICEF staff
member, Pierce Gerety, who was with the Geneva-based United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
As a sign of mourning, the U.N. flag in the courtyard of the
U.N. headquarters in New York was lowered to half-mast and the
national flags of all the 185 member states were taken down.  
</P>
</TEXT>
