<HEADLINE> European Shares Fall Sharply but off Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Major European stock markets
closed sharply lower, but off the day's lows after an overnight
fall on Wall Street and a fresh slide as the U.S. market opened on
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index ended 117.1 points lower at 5188.7. It
had stood 146.5 points down just a few minutes before trade ended.
The FTSE 250 was 63.2 down at 4648.8, and the FTSE Small-Cap 13.1
lower at 2068.2.
</P>
<P>
The Dow was around 100 points lower as London closed.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German stocks clambered off their lows, too,
encouraged by Wall Street's rebound from early lows, but remained
very weak on general global bearishness.
</P>
<P>
The electronically-traded Xetra Dax index finished at 4797,
down 151 after Germany's central bank left interest rates steady.
</P>
<P>
A Frankfurt-based trader said that while a retreat was expected
after Wednesday's gains, investors remain concerned in light of
Russia's economic and political tribulations.
</P>
<P>
While the weight of the Russian bear is felt in economies the
world over, it presses heaviest on near-neighbors like Germany,
whose bank sector has borne the brunt of investor concern over its
extensive credit exposure to Russia.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French stocks were down but off lows with investors
still sidelined and now focused on markets in Latin America. The
leading Cac-40 index closed at 3646, down 83 points.
</P>
<P>
The market took little notice of the Bank of France's
as-expected decision to hold interest rates steady.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, preliminary French gross domestic product expanded
by 0.7 percent in the second quarter and rose 3.0 percent
year-on-year. These increases were in line with expectations.
</P>
<P>
"People are concerned about Latin America" where a crisis is
"inevitable," one trader at a French bank was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The financial crises in Asia and Russian are spilling over to
Latin America where "the economic scenario hasn't cleared up," he
added.
</P>
<P>
As a result, "even the most daring (investors) have chilled,"
the trader noted. But he also said that investors aren't selling
off in panic despite the recent stock-market plunge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
