<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., UK Submit Draft Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States and
Britain on Thursday submitted to the Security Council a draft
resolution on Iraq, and the 15-member council is expected to
resume consultations on the matter early next week.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Hans Pahlgren, president of the Security
Council in September, briefed reporters on the first consultations
held by the Security Council in this month.
</P>
<P>
"That draft resolution is now being considered by delegations
and in capitals, and we will resume consultations on that matter
early next week," said Pahlgren, who assumed office of the
rotating council presidency on September 1.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution proposed the suspension of periodic
reviews of sanctions against Iraq until Baghdad resumes full
cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council every 60 days reviews the sanctions
imposed on Iraq following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait. The next
review is expected to take place next month.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, chief U.N. inspector Richard Butler told the
Security Council that Iraq had refused three times over the last
month to allow his inspectors to check sites they had visited
previously.
</P>
<P>
West diplomats on Thursday said that the Iraqi stance was
"totally acceptable" in a statement which echoed a U.N. resolution
calling for an Iraqi policy shift to fully work with the U.N.
Special Commission (UNSCOM) over weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced on August 5 to halt its cooperation with the
UNSCOM in a bid to reduce what it called American influence on the
inspection team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
