<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Bomber Order Linked to DPRK Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon denied on
Thursday that its "short-notice" order to send six heavy bombers
to Guam this weekend was linked to a new test of missiles by the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The Joint Chief of Staff sent a short-notice order to the Air
Force late on Wednesday that three batwing B-2 stealth bombers
and three eight-engine B-52s be sent to Andersen Air Force Base,
Guam, from bomber bases in Louisiana and Missouri. The order was
issued just two days after the DPRK's Taepo Dong 1 test missile
passed over Japan.
</P>
<P>
The defense officials said the mission was simply another in
a series of air power projection exercises and not meant as a
warning to Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
"It was not prompted by the North Korea missile test," one of
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
"They were not directly connected" with the DPRK's test of
the new missile, another official said. "But if people take
inferences that America can respond quickly with all of its
assets anywhere in the world, then so be it."
</P>
<P>
All the six planes, which will be refueled in the air during
non-stop flights to Guam, are capable of dropping bombs and
launching cruise missiles. They will likely take part in weapons
exercises at a range in the Northern Marianas Islands, the
officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
