<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BT Launches New Digital Internet Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- British Telecom Thursday
launched its new BT Highway mass market digital communication
service, which is designed to allow people to surf the Internet at
high speed and use the telephone simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
The service, to begin from September 15, will transform a
customer's existing telephone line into a new fast and
multi-functional digital Internet and multimedia connection, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
BT Highway offers customer choices of using combinations of
analogue or digital connections over a single telephone line,
which means families or small businesses could surf the Internet
or send e-mails and make calls at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Currently, users with a single analogue telephone line have to
disconnect from the Internet when they are using the phone.
</P>
<P>
The new service will operate at a minimum speed of 64 kilobits
per second, or a maximum of 128 kilobits per second, much faster
than the fastest modems working on ordinary telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
"BT Highway is a major step towards mass digitalisation of the
UK." Afshin Mohebbi, Managing Director of BT's Business Division,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Though Internet growth has been phenomenal, only 1.8 million UK
households are connected. BT hopes that its new service will help
bridge the gap.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to connect the majority of UK households with the
latest high-quality, high-capacity digital communications by the
year 2003." the company said.
</P>
<P>
At the moment ten percent of all telephone usage in the UK is
for data, but BT expects data to become the most important aspect
of the network some time before 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
