<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Finances Drinking Water Project for Nepali Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has agreed to grant a technical assistance of 600,000 U.S.
dollars to help the Nepali government design a small town water
supply and sanitation project for possible ADB financing, the bank
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The assistance aims to establish a water-supply and sanitation
sector plan and five-year investment programs for small towns in
Nepal and reach general agreement among the stakeholders on the
implementation and financing arrangements for the project, the
bank said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
It also aims at preparing feasibility studies and preliminary
designs for sample sub-projects and assisting the Department of
Water Supply and Sewerage in implementing drinking water quality
and sanitation standards, it said.
</P>
<P>
The technical assistance project is expected to start in
January 1999 and be completed in September 1999, it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank has been the lead development institution for rural
water supply and sanitation development in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, it has provided four concessional loans and seven
technical assistance grants totaling more than 65 million dollars
for rural water supply and sanitation development in the country,
the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"Small towns have emerged over the years along the major
national highways in the country which have not yet been covered
by any program in the water supply and sanitation sector," it
noted.
</P>
<P>
"The technical assistance is an initiative to address the water
supply and sanitation needs of the population living in these
emerging towns, which will help improve their health profile and
foster economic growth and social development in these
communities," it added.
</P>
<P>
Lack of safe drinking water is a big problem facing Nepal, in
particular the rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
