<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Statement on Successful Launch of Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) Thursday stood up for its
"internationally recognized right" of owing an artificial
satellite.
</P>
<P>
It criticized "hostile forces" for spreading "rumors" about the
alleged missile firing.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry spokesman said in a statement that the
satellite launch is DPRK's "one more fruit" of independent economy
and "a 100-percent product of Korean technology and efforts."
</P>
<P>
It gives pride and delight to the Korean nation and its
friends, it added.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, some people around the DPRK are "making a
fuss" about the satellite and remain ignorant of this "valuable
success of science and technology which will add to the common
treasure house of humanity."
</P>
<P>
Those people suspect it to be a ballistic missile
test-launching, express "apprehensions" and describe it as a
"serious event." Their rash behavior reminds one of the saying
"once bitten, twice shy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some people in the United States talk as if the DPRK satellite
launching has made it difficult for them to fulfill their
obligation under the DPRK-U.S. framework agreement, and try to
link this matter with food assistance which they described as a
purely humanitarian issue, it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement described Japan's behavior as "more intolerable."
It said the Japanese authorities, although having no information
on what happened, blindly accepted rumors about the ballistic
missile test-launching in the DPRK and threatened to bring the
issue to the U.N. Security Council and take "countermeasures."
</P>
<P>
The statement pointed out that before announcing that it would
"put off" negotiations for normalization of diplomatic ties, Japan
must not forget that it is the DPRK's right to demand apologies
and compensation for its past crimes.
</P>
<P>
Saying the launch and use of an artificial satellite is in line
with the trend of developing modern science and technology, the
satement said the DPRK has never criticized the United States and
Japan for having launched artificial satellites, though it is well
aware that the satellites have been used for espionage on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
