<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Concerned Over WHO Fund Cut for Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW Delhi, September 4 (Xinhua) -- India is concerned over a
proposed cut in World Health Organization (WHO) funds for the
South East Asia region, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The real issue is not the amount of money that has been
reduced, but the basis on which cuts have been proposed for the
countries in the South East Asia regioin, which are facing severe
health problems, PTI quoted health officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the case of India, which receives 15 million U.S. dollars
each year from WHO, the funds have been slashed by 9.75 percent,
or some 1.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
PTI said the funds are being diverted to Africa and East Europe
and Indian officials are worried that this diversion reflected a
lack of understanding of the disease burden of the region.
</P>
<P>
The officials said some countries have expressed their concern
over the issue to India which is to host the 16th conference of
health ministers of the region.
</P>
<P>
These countries hoped that the issue be discussed with WHO
Director General Bro Harlem Brundtlandt who is scheduled to arrive
in New Delhi Friday night to address the conference as well as the
51st session of the WHO regional committee for the South East Asia
region in the coming week. 
</P>
