<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Banks Rush to Buy Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan banks have set off
a panic dollar-buying spree Friday despite the announcement by the
government that the Russian financial crisis put limited influence
on the country.
</P>
<P>
The agitation was caused by the worry over the future of
Russia's financial crisis and inflation, the RanoRana newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
Although the National Bank, the only seller in the foreign
exchange market, has raised the exchange rate of the U.S. dollar
to local currency Tenge, the demand for dollar is experiencing
continuous increase.
</P>
<P>
In the past week, the daily volume of foreign exchange
transaction far exceeded the average level, with the highest
reaching 14.495 million dollars. The Tenge to dollar rate fell by
20 percentage points, floating at the high level of 78.50 to 79.91
to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, the future of the Kazakhstan monetary market will
be decided by the development of outside situation, economists
here said. 
</P>
