<HEADLINE> Thailand, Indonesia Fined for Fake Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Both Thailand and Indonesia
were each fined on Friday 40,000 US dollars for their fake match
in the Tiger Cup soccer tournament earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Football Federation, the regional body governing
football in South East Asia, imposed the fine after Indonesia
deliberately lost 3-2 to Thailand with a last-minute own goal on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Both teams were planning to appeal the decision while the
ASEAN will be looking at the rules of the competition to ensure
there is no repeat of the farcical scenes.
</P>
<P>
Thailand won the game in Ho Chi Minh City when an Indonesian
defender scored a deliberate own goal in injury time for his side
to finish second in Group A.
</P>
<P>
Neither team wanted to win the group in order not to play the
hosts in the semifinal by travelling from Ho Chi Minh City to
Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
However, neither team entered the final eventually as
Singapore defeated Indonesia 2-1 in the first semifinal while
Vietnam beat Thailand 3-0. 
</P>
