<HEADLINE> Clinton Confident of N. Irish Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Friday in Dublin he was confident about the prospects for
peace in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement at a press briefing following a meeting
with Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern in the Dublin Castle on the
second day of his visit to Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
Clinton hinted that he expected Northern Irish Protestant
leader David Trimble and his arch political rival, Sinn Fein
President Gerry Adams, to break another long-standing taboo next
week by meeting face to face for the first time.
</P>
<P>
"The statements in the last few days by Gerry Adams and Mr
Trimble's response make me quite hopeful about next week, and then
after that we'll just have to see where we go from there," BBC
quoted Clinton as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added that he hoped his current visit, the second in less
than three years, would help maintain the momentum for peace in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president also said the Irish peace could set an
example for warring peoples in the Middle East and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
"The potential impact of resolving this could wash over many
more people than live on this island," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the joint press briefing, Ahern paid tribute to Clinton for
his efforts in pushing forward peace process in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"What the president's visit has done is that it has got the
parties to move, on what might have taken weeks and months, over a
very short period," the Irish prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will visit an American computer company near Dublin
airport in the afternoon. On Saturday he intends to fulfil another
pledge made on that visit -- to play a round of golf at
Ballybunion before heading back to Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
