<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plan Launched to Revitalize Angola's Rural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A plan has been mapped out in
Angola to revitalize the war-torn rural economy from 1998 to
2000.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which was forwarded by the Angolan Agricultur and
Rural Development Ministry, is to achieve its goal by heavily
investing in rural economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the "Symposium on Current Situation and Future of
Angolan Economy", which is being held here, the plan involves a
rural loan system by the government, the construction of
agricultural infrastructure with irrigation system as the major
works and the strengthening of supply system of means of
production.
</P>
<P>
To encourage home and foreign investors, especially private
financial institutions to invest in agriculture, the new loan
system would allow those who want to borrow money to use their
farming land as mortgage.
</P>
<P>
A preferential two-year loan with a rate of less than 7.5
percent would be guaranteed according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
The government would give priority in building irrigation
projects in provinces like Luand, Bengo and Benguela.
</P>
<P>
It would also promote the breeding of farm cattle and develop
local industry making farm tools for the household and
labor-intensive economy.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of foreign investment and the restoration of
traditional export-oriented coffee and sugar-cane planting would
be encouraged, according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
Angola used to be a big farm country, ranking third in coffee
export in the world, with self-sufficient grain production. But
long years of civil war has rendered in a lot of land abandoned
and farmers fleeding as refugees.
</P>
<P>
The country needs about 470,000 tons of grain from outside in
1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
