<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Successfully Launches First Artificial Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) sent its first artificial satellite into
orbit on August 31, transmitting revolutionary songs back to the
Earth, the Korean Central News Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
A three-stage rocket carrying the satellite blasted off in the
direction of 86 degrees at a launching station in the Musudan-ri
village, Hwadae County, North Hamgyong Province at about 12
a.m. local time (0300 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The satellite went into orbit four minutes 53 seconds later.
</P>
<P>
The first stage of the rocket was separated 95 seconds after
lift-off and fell on the open waters of the Sea of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The splash spot is 253 kilometers off the eastern coast of
DPRK, at 40 degrees 51 minutes north latitude and 139 degrees 40
minutes east longitude.
</P>
<P>
The second stage opened the capsule in 144 seconds, separated
itself from the rocket in 266 seconds. It fell on the open waters
of the Pacific Ocean 1,646 kilometers off the launching site, at
40 degrees 13 minutes north latitude and 149 degrees 7 minutes
east longitude.
</P>
<P>
The third stage put the satellite into orbit 27 seconds after
the separation of the second stage.
</P>
<P>
The satellite is flying along an oval orbit 218.82 kilometers
in the nearest distance from the Earth and 6,978.2 kilometers in
the farthest distance. Its period is 165 minutes 6 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The satellite reportedly carries with it sounding equipment,
with an aim to promoting scientific research for peaceful use of
outer space.
</P>
<P>
The report said that it is also instrumental in confirming the
calculation basis for launching practical satellites in the future.
</P>
<P>
The satellite is now transmitting revolutionary hymns "Song of
General Kim Il Sung" and "Song of General Kim Jong Il" and the
Morse signals "Juche Korea" in 27 Mhz.
</P>
<P>
The satellite and the rocket were 100 percent made by DPRK
scientists and technicians, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China Eyes Deficit Policy on Economic Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government today
issued the first round of 10-year treasury bonds totaling 100
billion yuan in a bid to support infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
Finance officials and noted economists agree that the
measure will promote a new round of investment and will have a
positive impact on the nation's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"The bonds and an equal volume of bank loans as supporting
projects funds will contribute more than two percentage points to
this year's GDP growth," according to Finance Minister Xiang
Huaicheng.
</P>
<P>
The 50 billion yuan in bonds set for issue as part of this
year's state budget will raise the financial deficit from the
original 46 billion yuan to 96 billion yuan. The figure will
considerably exceeding debt and deficit ceilings ratified during
the first session of the Ninth National People's Congress,
according to Xiang.
</P>
<P>
Prominent economists contend that current deflationary
conditions, combined with increased net withdrawals of cash money
from circulation, and the serious deficiency in capital for
construction projects make it necessary for the government to
engage in deficit spending in order to increase inputs for
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
China's economic growth rate for the first half of 1998 stood at
only seven percent due to the negative impact of the Asian
financial crisis in the first half of 1998. The six-month figure
was substantially lower than the projects target set earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government thus decided to invest heavily in
infrastructure projects to stimulate the economy. As a result, a
five-fold investment growth was registered for water conservancy
projects, with a corresponding 2.8-fold rise for urban
construction and a 17.5-fold increase for grain reserve storage
projects.
</P>
<P>
Yang Qixian, deputy director of the Chinese Society for
Research on Restructuring the Economic System, noted that
investments will be the major contributor to annual targets due to
sluggish exports and domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
"The treasury bond issue will create at least two million
additional job opportunities, and large investments in
infrastructure projects will improve working and living conditions
for Chinese citizens." said Yang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China Eyes Deficit Policy on Economic Growth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Agricultural Bank of China (ABC) and the Construction Bank
of China (CBC) have each purchased bonds valued at 20 billion
yuan. The latter plans to provide additional funds totalling 29
billion yuan for post and telecommunications, power generation and
urban construction projects.
</P>
<P>
ABC Vice-President Li Dianjun said that pumping funds raised
from the bond issue into infrastructure construction will help
reduce loan risks and improve the overall operations of commercial
banks.
</P>
<P>
Xiang discounted the possibility that the bond issue will spark
a new round of inflation. He pointed out that the volume of
currency in circulation is under control, the nation enjoys a
negative inflation rate and, in addition, there is ample room to
fulfill the loan quota set by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Officials and economists are also bullish on the government's
ability to retire debt, and they share the view that the 100
billion yuan will occupy only a small proportion of China's debt
in this decade.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the overall efficiency of the national economy
will rise over the next three years in line with the anticipated
successful reform of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
China also plans to establish a debt repayment fund, according
to Xiang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
