<HEADLINE> Vote on Chernomyrdin' Nomination Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma decided
on Friday to postpone the second round of vote on Viktor
Chernomyrdin's nomination as prime minister to next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The postponement was made at a request of the Russian president.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, or lower house of parliament, took the
decision with 294 votes for, 51 against and three abstaining.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the State Duma Gennady Seleznyov had a
conversation with President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
The president suggested to hold a roundtable meeting of leaders
of the Duma factions and deputy groups, as well as members of the
Federation Council on Monday morning, and then hold the debate on
premier's nomination later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also suggested that a roundtable be held among
representatives of Duma groups, the Federation Council and
political parties to discuss appointment of the new premier.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party faction in the Duma agreed to take part in
the roundtable meeting to see if the president will offer
something new, according to Chairman of the Communist Party
Gennady Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing opposition in the State Duma, said Zyuganov, will
reject Chernomyrdin on the second ballot, and has not believed and
does not believe any promises from the president.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Communist Party agreed to hold consultations
with Yeltsin only because the situation in the country is
"extremely tense."
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Federation Council, or upper house of
parliament, Friday passed a resolution in favor of Chernomyrdin's
appointment as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Before the Duma session, Yeltsin had a meeting with
Chernomyrdin in the Kremlin to hear the results of visit by the
acting prime minister to the Federation Council.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin on Friday made a report on social-political
situation in the country at a meeting of the Federation Council,
where he asked the deputies to support him and give its consent to
urgent actions of the government.
</P>
<P>
He is confident that he will be supported by most governors
and be approved by deputies of the Duma.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was named by the Russian president as prime
minister on August 24 after the government led by Kiriyenko was
sacked and his nomination was rejected by a majority of the Duma
deputies at the first ballot on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
