<HEADLINE> S. Korea Beats China at Asian Cup Ice Hockey Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korea edged China 1-0 on
a sole goal by centre forward Shim Eui-Sik in the opener of the
Asian Cup ice hockey tournament on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The goal came 15:25 into the third period as Chinese keeper
Geng Hua fell on the ice after saving a Korean onslaught when
Shim fired home a Kim Chang-Bun pass from close range in front of
the goal.
</P>
<P>
It was a sweet revenge for the Koreans, who lost to China 0-6
when they played each other last time at the World Championships
Pool C match in March.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese showed better formation and passing play, while
the Koreans retaliated with power play, but both sides fell short
of shooting accuracy in the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese team is always stronger and better than us and we
rarely defeated them. Today, we tried to beat them mentally and
physically. We were able to stop their rhythm," said Korean head
coach Kim Sea-Il.
</P>
<P>
Chinese coach Wang Jin-Gang said: "This is only our second
game since we started practicing together three weeks ago and my
players were a bit nervous in the first period. Our keeper did
his job very well giving only one goal."
</P>
<P>
China will face Japan on Saturday at the Higashi Fushimi Ice
Arena in the three-nation event.
</P>
<P>
The winners will take a berth in the World Championships Pool
A, while the other two teams will play in Pool C. 
</P>
