<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV Carriers Must Tell Partners: Canadian Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of Canada has
ruled that people carrying the AIDS virus must tell their partners
about it.
</P>
<P>
The top court, calling such behavior dangerous and deplorable,
said HIV carriers who have sex with unwitting partners can be
found guilty of assault.
</P>
<P>
The court made the ground-breaking ruling Thursday in ordering
a new trial for Henry Cuerrier of British Columbia Provice, an
HIV-positive man acquitted of aggravated assault after having sex
with two women unaware of his illness.
</P>
<P>
"In this case the complainants were exposed to a significant
risk of serious harm to their health," Justice Peter Cory wrote
for a majority of the court.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, the potentially fatal consequences are far more
invidious and graver than many other actions prohibited by the
Criminal Code. The risks of infection are so devastating that
there is a real and urgent need to provide a measure of protection
for those in the position of the complainants," said Justice Cory.
</P>
<P>
Henry Cuerrier tested positive for the virus in August
1992. But he continued to have unprotected sex without telling
partners he was HIV-positive, even after a public health officer
ordered him to use condoms and inform lovers of his illness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
