<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SES Announces Halt of CLOB Malaysian Share Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 4 (Xinhua) --The Stock Exchange of
Singapore (SES) Friday announced that trading of Malaysian stocks
on Singapore's over-the-counter market known as CLOB will cease.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, SES said that after extensive
consultation with the industry, the SES has concluded that it will
no longer be viable for it to provide Singapore investors with the
facility to trade Malaysian shares on CLOB.
</P>
<P>
The SES also set forth an arrangement under which trading of
Malaysian shares on CLOB will resume for one week from a date to
be determined and thereafter trading of Malaysian stocks will
cease.
</P>
<P>
The SES statement came after Malaysia announced measures to
curb capital outflows and placed a ban on overseas transactions in
its currency and stocks.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian Central Depository announced new measures to
regulate the trading of Malaysian shares on August 31. This was
followed by Bank Negara Malaysia's announcement of foreign
exchange controls on September 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Singapore and Malaysia have been disputing over the trading of
Malaysian shares on CLOB. Malaysia holds that CLOB has been
detrimental to Malaysia because it has facilitated the short
selling of Malaysian shares and taken away business from brokers
of the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange. But Singapore argued that the
existence of CLOB has benefited Malaysian shares as CLOB has
increased Singapore investor interest in these shares and provided
liquidity and price support to them.
</P>
<P>
The SES said it will continue to develop new Singapore and
Asian products so as to provide investors with a wide range of
investment alternatives and strengthen its position in Asian
capital market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
