<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Donation Supports Beijing Suburban School, Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A primary school and hospital
built with donations from two senior members of Lions Club
International in Hong Kong opened today in suburbs of Beijing, the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The school in Jinjiabao Township, Yanqing County, was built
with a donation of 540,000 yuan (67,500 US dollars) from Tak-Sum
Ho, director of the City Lions Clubs of Hong Kong of Lions Clubs
International District 303, Hong Kong and Macao. The local
government allocated an additional 660,000 yuan for the project.
</P>
<P>
The spacious facility will provide children of six nearby
villages bright classrooms and more space for extracurricular
activities.
</P>
<P>
The hospital, the only facility of its kind in Henanzhai
Township, Miyun County, was constructed with a donation of 650,000
yuan from Wong Chung Ying, former inspector general of the Lions
Clubs International District 303, Hong Kong and Macao. The local
government equipped the facility at a cost of 1.35 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The two townships carry official designations as poor areas.
</P>
<P>
Members of Lions Clubs International District 303, Hong Kong
and Macao, have donated over 11 million yuan for for Beijing
projects in recent years. The funds have been used to construct an
eye hospital, four township hospitals and a primary school in poor
suburban areas around the capital. 
</P>
