<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pak Economy Beset With Difficulty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's economy, beset
with difficulties, is getting worse because of an acute shortage
of revenue due to economic sanctions imposed on it by some
countries after its May nuclear tests and the poor export
performance.
</P>
<P>
Despite assurances by the government of an early improvement in
the economy, this South Asian nation's financial picture is
getting murkier along with the larger economic scene.
</P>
<P>
The most conspicuous feature of this negative development is
the ever increasing borrowing from domestic commercial banks by
the central and provincial governments.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the government has raised a total of
 30.47 billion rupees (46 rupees equal one U.S. dollar) through
bank borrowing or printing of money in the first five weeks of the
1998-99 fiscal year beginning July 1.
</P>
<P>
The budget ceiling for the government's bank borrowing in the
current fiscal year is 12 billion rupees and the total bank credit
for the fiscal year is 56 billion rupees.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the four provincial governments are reported to
have borrowed 9.37 billion rupees from the state bank as the
central government does not have enough funds to release to them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, borrowing from commercial banks by the private
sector in the same period stood at 32.8 billion rupees, indicating
reduced industrial and commercial activities which would result in
lower tax revenues, reduced exports and shrinking employment
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, with its economy largely dependent on foreign
assistance, can not afford a lower economic growth, particularly a
lower industrial growth. Yet such low borrowing by the private
sector also means financial losses to banks.
</P>
<P>
Official revenues have fallen sharply because of lower tax
payments and poor performance of the export sector. Imports in
July dropped by almost 50 percent, leading to declines in customs
revenues and sales tax.
</P>
<P>
With an unfavorable balance of payments position in years,
Pakistan has long been looking toward the export arena to boost
its incomes.
</P>
<P>
Export, as the pulse of any economy, plays a crucial role in
Pakistan's gross domestic product. However, for many years,
Pakistan's export growth has been sluggish and very little money
has entered the country in terms of foreign exchange to finance
its heavy debt of 30.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the 1997-98 fiscal year, Pakistan's growth rate of export
was only 2.61 percent against the targeted 15 percent. And this
growth was registered mainly due to an increase in the exports of
rice and raw cotton.
</P>
<P>
During last fiscal year, manufactured goods declined by a
significant margin and textile export which makes up 65 percent of
the country's total exports went down from 81 percent to 78
percent.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, Pakistani exporters have faced problems abroad
but this year a number of elements have brought endless
frustration to the exporters and seriously affected exports.
</P>
<P>
The worsening law and order situation in the commercial city of
Karachi, the growing number of strikes and power supply
disruptions affected the industrial units in Karachi, causing
billions of dollars in losses.
</P>
<P>
Local economists believe that to achieve a favorable economic
growth rate and balance of payments position, it is of great
importance to develop the export industry. For this end, long-term
planning is crucial at this point. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke090454 - Flood Situation May Aggravate Further in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The overall flood situation in
Bangladesh is likely to aggravate further Friday with rise of
water levels in three major river basins due to the active monsoon
and impact of full moon, the official BSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The flood situation along the Brahmaputra-Jamuna and districts
along the Padma River may deteriorate further, the Flood
Forecasting and Warning Center (FFWC) was quoted as saying in its
forecast for the next 24 hours beginning 09:00 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the downstream of the Meghna basin from
Bhairab Bazar and in the central part of the country as well as
around the capital city of Dhaka is expected to worsen further,
the FFWC cautioned.
</P>
<P>
The FFWC, however, stated that the flood situation in the upper
part of the Meghna basin may continue to improve.
</P>
<P>
The on-going devastating flood, which has lasted for nearly two
months and hit about 60 percent of the country's area, has so far
affected more than 21.5 million people in 45 of the country's 64
districts, with the death toll rising to 451, according to the
latest figures issued by the Ministry of Relief and Disaster
management.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the flood has also damaged more than 227,000 hectares
of crops, more than 377,000 houses, 9,347 kilometers of roads,
4,121 kilometers of embankments, 4,652 bridges and culverts and
1,052 education institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
