<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Media Addresses Sexual Harassment (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chen Kuizun, member of the National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, recently proposed attaching related amendments
to appropriate laws.
</P>
<P>
When the NPC deliberated the draft Law on Doctors in June, Chen
suggested that individuals guilty of sexual harassment should be
subject to punishment clearly defined by law.
</P>
<P>
Consultation and complaint records have accounted for a mere
one percent of calls to a Beijing hot line for women established
some six years ago, according to Wang Xingjuan, director of the
Beijing Institute of Women. Wang made the comment in a letter to
the Nanfang Weekend Newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Many women complain they have no place to turn when seeking
redress for harassment cases.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for 1996 show that over half of sexual harassment
cases involved the work place, with 36 percent of the total
involving high-level male officials and an additional 14 percent
attributed to male colleagues.
</P>
<P>
The majority cases involved single women under the age of
30. Fifty percent of victims reported inappropriate physical
advances and a number of women claimed they were forced to have
sex with male colleagues.
</P>
<P>
"Males bent on harassment most often entice female subordinates
with higher wages or promotions, and in some cases threaten fire
women or otherwise smear their reputations," according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
The rising number of complaints obviously indicates the urgent
need for legislation, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
"Sexual harassment is a serious subject," according to Chen,
who also serves as vice chairman of the Jiangxi People's Congress
Standing Committee. Chen's remark was carried in report released
by Jiangxi Daily.
</P>
<P>
No precedent exists for China to attach sexual harassment
articles to existing laws. However, the legislature has the option
to introduce new regulations and stipulate punishment in special
laws and to formulate a separate law at a later date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
