<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Promises to Take Care of Elderly in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwa of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) said
Friday that the SAR government will continue its efforts to
promote the elderly health services.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the launching ceremony of the Elderly Health
Services of the Department of Health, Tung said the government
shall work even harder to further honor the pledges of "caring for
the elderly" put forward by him in the Policy Address delivered
last year.
</P>
<P>
"To achieve our goal of providing a feeling of health and
worthiness, we must ensure that the elderly are physically and
mentally healthy," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
With rapid socio-economic development, growing sophistication
in medical technology and continuous improvement in environmental
hygiene, the life expectancy in Hong Kong is increasing.
</P>
<P>
At present, the number of people aged 65 and above exceeds
600,000 and accounts for about 10 percent of the total
population. It is forecast that the population of the elderly in
the SAR will reach 840,000 in 10 years' time.
</P>
<P>
"The new Elderly Health Services are hence launched by the
Department of Health with the aim of fulfilling our policy
objective of caring for the elderly," the chief executive said.
</P>
<P>
Seven elderly health centers have been set up and 7 elderly
health visiting teams have started reaching out for the elderly
since July 2 this year.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that in the coming 19 months, the government will set
up 11 additional elderly health centers and 11 additional elderly
health visiting teams so that each of the 18 districts within the
SAR shall have its own center and visiting team.
</P>
<P>
Professionals like doctors, nurses, dietitians, occupational
therapists, physiotherapists and clinical psychologists are
working together at each center to look after the various needs of
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
The elderly health visiting teams help to promote the concept
and awareness of health care among the elderly living in the
community and at homes for the aged, and offer more assistance to
the family of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
"I am glad to know that the membership of the 7 elderly health
centers, which started operation in July, has now reached 70
percent of the expected size," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
It proves that the elderly health services are generally
welcomed by the elderly, he added.
</P>
<P>
It is encouraging to note that within a short period of time,
the Department of Health is able to provide such well-received
services, which cater for the needs of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
"I have confidence that with the concerted effort and full
cooperation of all parties concerned, the elderly of Hong Kong
will lead a healthier, richer and more meaningful life," Tung
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
