<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Nosedive on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to
nose-dive on Singapore Stock Market Friday as market remained
dampened by worries over Malaysia's new rules in its currency and
stock transactions.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) lost 7.56 points to
805.04 points with banking stocks languishing on prevailing
concerns over their Malaysian exposure.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover declined to 117.75 million units valued at
157.42 million Singapore dollars (89.95 million U.S. dollars).
Gainers outnumbered losers by 126 to 87 with 373 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
SingTel remained the most active stock of the day with a volume
of 10.14 million stocks traded. It was followed by OCBC F that had
6.47 million units done. EnerSave was next with 5.77 million
counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Asean was the top gainer of the day as it gained 90 cents to
close at 3.90 U.S. dollars. Creative 50 went up by 30 cents to
close at 17.10 Singapore Dollars. ICB inched up 23 cents to end at
1.65 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Jurship was the biggest loser of the day as it lost 45 cents to
end at 7.05 Singapore dollars. GE Life was down 30 cents to close
at 6.70 Singapore dollars. NatElec slid by 26 cents to finish at
3.12 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said uncertainty over Malaysia's capital control and
ban on equity trading overseas remained strong.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of Malaysian shares on Singapore's
over-the-counter market known as CLOB thinned volumes since the
actively traded stocks account for some 40 per cent of the l
volume, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
