<HEADLINE> Plan for South East Kowloon Development Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) has approved a plan to
develop the ex-Kai Tak Airport site and the nearby Kowloon Bay
areas into a strategic growth area called "City within a City."
</P>
<P>
The whole South East Kowloon Development (SEKD) covers about
579 hectares of land, with about 280 hectares of it coming from
the Kai Tak Airport site and the remaining 299 hectares to be
developed from Kowloon Bay and parts of the adjacent districts.
</P>
<P>
According to a government spokesman, the whole project with an
estimated cost of about 36 billion HK dollars (4.6 billion U.S.
dollars) will be completed in 2016.
</P>
<P>
Upon its completion, the area will house about 320,000 people,
with first population intake commencing 2003. A total of 123
hectares of land has been reserved for housing development.
</P>
<P>
Community facilities such as schools, clinics, recreation
centers, police stations to serve the designed population will be
provided.
</P>
<P>
The implementation works of the development project will create
about 14,000 job opportunities, and more than 90,000 jobs will be
created in South East Kowloon, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, the SEKD will also boost our economy by enabling the
implementation of strategic infrastructural projects that will
serve the development needs of Hong Kong," he added.
</P>
<P>
The SEKD will be implemented in four development packages --
North Apron of Kai Tak Airport; Reclamation of Kai Tak Nullah/Kwun
Tong Typhoon Shelter; Kowloon Bay Reclamation Phase 1; and Kowloon
Bay Reclamation Phase 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
