<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Plays Down Expectation for U.S. Envoy's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat played down Friday the upcoming visit by U.S. peace envoy
Dennis Ross, saying the gaps between the Israeli and Palestinian
sides remain "very wide."
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remarks in Gaza upon his return from South
Africa, where he attended a summit of The Non-aligned Movement,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Israel and the Palestinians are close to a deal on
accepting the U.S. initiative calling for a 13.1 percent Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank, Arafat said: "Actually they
(Israelis) are saying so, but the gaps are still very wide."
</P>
<P>
During a visit to Northern Ireland Thursday, U.S. President
Bill Clinton announced he was sending Ross back to the
Middle East next week to help the sides to advance the stalled
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here said that Ross is expected to arrive in
the region on next Tuesday, or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ross' return was called for by both the Israelis and
Palestinians, who have failed to clinch a deal over the long
overdue redeployment since they resumed direct talks on July 19.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding obstacle blocking an agreement was believed to
be the dispute over the scope of the pullback.
</P>
<P>
While the Palestinian side has already accepted the
U.S. initiative on a 13.1 percent pullback, Israel first rejected
the scope citing security concerns, then demanded that 3 percent
of the proposed territories be turned into natural reserves to
restrict the Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
Still, Arafat has rejected the Israeli compromise, ruling out
further Palestinian compromise on the U.S. initiative since it is
already a compromise in the view of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Optimism surfaced in the past week for a breakthrough as media
reports disclosed that Israeli and Palestinian officials continued
secret negotiations on clinching a deal and made significant
progress.
</P>
<P>
A senior Palestinian official was quoted by Israel Radio as
saying Friday that a draft agreement had been reached in
principle, but internal disputes among Palestinian officials have
prevented it from being finalized.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that senior Palestinian officials, including
Arafat's deputy Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) and senior Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat, have expressed their objection to the
draft agreement.
</P>
<P>
The same Palestinian official said 10 secret meetings were
held in the past two weeks between the two sides, three of which
held between Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Abu
Ala, speaker of the Palestinian Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
The other meetings were held between Abu Ala and Netanyahu's
confidant and attorney Yitzhak Molcho, some of which were attended
by Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, a dove in the
government.
</P>
<P>
In return for its agreement to accept the 13 percent
withdrawal, Israel wants to obtain the Palestinian promise to
crack tougher down on Islamic militants and revise the clauses in
the Palestinian Covenant calling for Israeli destruction.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, media adviser to Netanyahu, has said that
a deal would be possible if the Palestinians were prepared to
meet their security commitments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes on Positive Note </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar shot
above the 59 U.S. cent level for the first time in two weeks
Friday, buoyed from stronger commodity prices and Australia's
recent better than expected growth.
</P>
<P>
The local currency gained more than three U.S. cents over the
week to close trading Friday at 59.06 U.S. cents from 55.99 U.S.
cents last Friday and 58.36 U.S. cents in Sydney Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The rebound in the domestic unit from its new record post-float
low of 55.30 U.S. cents, recorded on August 28, was assisted by
higher commodity prices, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Treasurer Peter Costello also released figures this week
showing that the economy grew by 3.9 percent in the fiscal year of
1997-1998 ending on June 30, 1998, exceeding the budget forecast
of 3.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the cross rates, the Australian dollar was at 79.74 Japanese
yen from 79.63 yen and was buying 1.0237 German marks from 1.0161
marks. 
