<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
closed lower Friday as investors swapped from industrial stocks to
oversold resource stocks.
</P>
<P>
The sharemarket would have fallen even further if not for a
slight strengthening of the Australian dollar, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index dropped 9.3 points to
2,504.0 after trading within a range of 2,490.6 and 2,521.0 during
the day.
</P>
<P>
"The rise in the dollar cushioned our market from falling the
amount it usually would have with a 100 point drop on Wall
Street," Macquarie Equities client adviser Rob Graham said.
</P>
<P>
The volatile Australian dollar pushed up through the key level
of 59.00 U.S. cents for the first time in two weeks Friday to
close at 59.06 U.S. cents from 58.38 U.S. cents Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index tumbled 34.4 points to 4,408.2, while
the all resources index firmed 14.3 to 966.4.
</P>
<P>
Resource stocks were also buoyed Friday by generally stronger
metals prices overnight with resources giant BHP climbing 13.6
cents to almost 12.87 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Anglo-Australian mining giant Rio Tinto went against the trend,
sliding 4.2 cents to 17.70 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks were stronger almost across the board, with the
gold index soaring 51.7 to 933.2 points on the back of a surge in
the price of the precious metal.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney closed Friday at
285.55 U.S. dollars an ounce, a big leap from Thursday's 278.65
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Two of the major bank stocks took a battering, with National
Australia Bank sliding 55 cents to 20.95 Australian dollars and
Westpac bank shedding 24 cents to 9.00 Australian dollars, both
helping drag the bank index 67.1 points lower to 5,419.9.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank gained three cents to 8.55 Australian dollars and
Commonwealth Bank of Australia firmed 8.4 cents to just over 19.33
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 260.85 million stocks traded for 862.03
million Australian dollars (509.11 million U.S. dollars), with
rising stocks outnumbering falling stocks 539 to 472 and 371
stocks remaining steady. 
</P>
