<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Warned to Mind Post-Waldner Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Sportswriter Wang Zijiang
</P>
<P>
JI'NAN, CHINA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Once all-time great
Jan-ove Waldner retired, a powerful table tennis empire Sweden
would vanish from the world. Then table tennis will be the
monopoly of China, the Scandinavian nation's traditional rival.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese fans hope it comes true.
</P>
<P>
But it's impossible, warned Kiell-Ake Waldner, Jan-Ove's
brother and coach of the national women's team.
</P>
<P>
The 34-year-old Kiell-Ake, two years older than Jan-Ove, said
they have enough young hopeful players and Sweden never lacks
table tennis talents.
</P>
<P>
"In Sweden, there are more than 1,000 table tennis clubs. More
than 10,000 players often take part in big tournaments. All of
them want to play in international arena, not just for fun," said
Kiell-Ake, who was competing in the ongoing Chinese Grand Prix
here with his players.
</P>
<P>
Considering the fact that Sweden has only a population of nine
million, it's an impressive figure.
</P>
<P>
The coach said that Sweden has a long tradition of playing
table tennis, it will remain a force to reckon with even after
his brother retired.
</P>
<P>
"In 1971 when Stellan Bengtsson, another great paddler in
Sweden's history retired, many people also thought the Sweden
will never win the world champion again. But Waldner made it,"
said Kiell-Ake, who took over the national team last year.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, Sweden won three successive team titles in
1989, 1991 and 1993. But besides Jan-Ove, Peter Karlsson and
Jorgen Persson, there is no sign to show they have young talents
to help maintain Sweden's status as a table tennis powerhouse in
the post-Waldner era.
</P>
<P>
"It is because the three veterans are still in good form,"
Kiel-Ake said. "The young players haven't many chances to compete
in big international tournaments. But if they retired, the young
will get mature very soon."
</P>
<P>
He said that it will not take a long time before a young Swede
emerges to become a new world champion as long as he is confident.
</P>
<P>
"My brother said to himself when he was very young that he can
do better than Bengtsson. And now he has become the most
successful player," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jan-Ove Waldner, the world's only male paddler who won a grand
slam of the world championships, Olympics and World Cup titles,
did not enter the Grand Prix because of a "tough schedule".
</P>
<P>
The current world champion, a second-round loser to world NO.
40 Peter Franz of Germany in last week's Austalia Open, skipped
the event to prepare for the European Masters Championships next
week, Kiell-Ake said.
</P>
<P>
Jan-Ove took part in the Chinese Grand Prix in 1992 and 1995,
only to be defeated by Chinese young players on both occasions.
But his brother denied his withdrawal this time was to avoid a
third humiliation by the host players.
</P>
<P>
"He was very, very tough mentally," the older brother said.
"It doesn't matter where he plays."
</P>
<P>
So far, the coach said, Waldner has not thought of retiring
from the sport that he began to play at the age of six.
</P>
<P>
"Perhaps when he feels he can not win a world champion or when
he has not strong motivation, he will call it quit." the brother
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
