<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Proposes Fuel-Economy Labelling for New Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
required on Friday European Union member states to provide
consumers with fuel-economy information about new cars.
</P>
<P>
The proposed requirement, designed as an integral part of the
15-nation union's strategy to reduce carbon dioxide emissions,
aims at making fuel-economy information available to consumers in
four ways.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the European Union,
required that a label should be attached to all cars at the point
of sale; a fuel-economy guide must be available free of charge on
new car market; a poster containing the fuel efficiency and carbon
dioxide emissions information should be available at the dealers',
and official fuel consumption information should be included in
promotional literature.
</P>
<P>
European Environment Commissioner Ritt Bjerregaard said that
the aim of the commission's proposed requirement is to provide
potential purchasers of new passenger cars with the relevant
information on fuel consumption so as to influence their choice
toward more fuel efficient models.
</P>
<P>
Consumer choices are based on factors such as lifestyle and
personal needs but many consumers might be unaware of the
significant variation in fuel consumption between similar cars and
even between cars in the same model range.
</P>
<P>
Carbon dioxide emissions from passenger cars now account for
half of all carbon dioxide emissions from the transport sector and
approximately 12 percent of carbon dioxide emissions from all
sources in the European Union, according to EU statistics.
</P>
<P>
Carbon dioxide emissions from the transport sector are expected
to continue to increase between now and the year 2010 and the
increase could undermine the European Union's commitments made at
the 1997 Kyoto World Environment Conference, commission officials.
</P>
<P>
The commission has set out 120 grams of carbon dioxide emission
per kilometer run by passenger cars as the benchmark for 2005 for
the new car fleet.
</P>
<P>
The commission has also decided to conclude an environmental
agreement with the European Automobile Manufacturers Association
as a further contribution toward achieving the objective of carbon
dioxide emissions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
