<HEADLINE> Chinese Media Addresses Sexual Harassment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Tuesday edition of a
popular Beijing-based newspaper carried a special report advising
female employs to avoid "coquettish behavior in the office, dress
appropriately, fulfill all job requirements and refrain from
discussing personal affairs with male colleagues."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, delegates to the ongoing Eighth National Congress of
Chinese Women have actively engaged in heated discussions
concerning sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
"Sexual harassment issues have surfaced throughout history and
have increasing concern in recent years." according to the Beijing
Youth Daily which has carried two in-depth commentaries on related
topics over the past month.
</P>
<P>
Women have gained an increasing awareness about male colleagues
sometimes making indecent and insulting remarks.
</P>
<P>
A number of other influential newspapers have also exhibited
great interest in the subject.
</P>
<P>
"Sexual harassment cases represent only the tip of the iceberg
in modern China," according to one south china newspaper, which
also addressed the possibility of related legislation.
</P>
<P>
On July 22, Shanghai Oriental Television carried a live talk
show featuring well-known legal scholars, attorneys and women
rights advocates. The panel called for the enactment of sexual
harassment legislation at the earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
The Guizhou City Newspaper, a popular publication in
southwestern Guizhou Province, published a lengthy commentary
detailing sexual harassment in the entertainment field.
</P>
<P>
The report claimed that sexual harassment is common in the
field. However, the report played down the severity of related
acts and noted that the law fails to stipulate punishment for
related conduct.
</P>
</TEXT>
