<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Province Guards Against Hemorrhagic Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Health Department of
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province has issued an emergency
circular requiring the flooded areas to guard against an epidemic
of hemorrhagic fever.
</P>
<P>
According to a Ministry of Health official, hemorrhagic fever
is spread among mice and enters the human body through agents such
as mites.
</P>
<P>
The mice population in the flood-stricken areas has risen
sharply, and the chance of contact with mice has been greatly
increased, so many regions in the province face the danger of an
outbreak of this disease, the health official said.
</P>
<P>
Experts say men in their prime are most likely to contract
hemorrhagic fever, a very complicated condition with a high
fatality rate. There is no effective treatment for this disease.
</P>
<P>
The circular asks that great attention be paid to the
prevention and control of the disease. Health departments are
expected to make scientific reports on the disease situation and
offer suggestions to local governments.
</P>
<P>
It is also required that the mice be wiped out, and
vaccinations offered to people in susceptible regions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
