<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 330,000 Industrial Workers Laid Off in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 330,000 workers of the
Thai industrial sector were laid off between January 1997 and July
this year, the Labor Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The number will reach 400,000 at the end of this year as the
economic slump continues, the ministry said in a report available
Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, 20,000 to 30,000 employees of the
industrial sector will lose jobs each month, so the number of
laid-off industrial workers since last year will rocket to 400,000
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The report said a total of 165,845 workers were sacked last
year and about 170,000 others lost jobs between January and July
this year.
</P>
<P>
Out of all 17 industries, the automobile, property development
and construction, cleaning and security service, and electronics
industries ranked tops in terms of the number of laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing and export industries are facing problems of
unskilled labor, liquidity, high import tariffs and slow tax
refund process, as well as lack of overseas markets, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the laid-off industrial workers, Thailand has
about 1.7 million other unemployed people in other sectors. The
total number is expected to jump to 3 million next year as the
economic crisis worsens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
