<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Car Sales Dip in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- August proved a tougher month
for sales of new cars and trucks in Australia but retailers would
still be smiling at the underlying strength in the vehicle market.
</P>
<P>
In its latest sales bulletin, the Federal Chamber of Automotive
Industries (FCAI) said Friday 64,965 new vehicles were sold last
month, down 8.5 percent from 71,040 in July.
</P>
<P>
But the result was still up 15.7 percent on the 56,123 sold in
August last year and put demand over the first eight months of
1998 up 16.1 percent to 535,585 units.
</P>
<P>
The market's performance also seemed to go against suggestions
the continuing Asian crisis, concerns over the introduction of
taxation changes and fears of interest rate rises might force a
significant downturn.
</P>
<P>
Some slowdown was highly likely in the remaining months but
most industry analysts and car companies were still tipping a
total market for the year of about 780,000, a record result and up
about 60,000 units on 1997.
</P>
<P>
The FCAI said it believed total sales would reach 790,000 units
with all sectors except sports cars showing an improvement this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
