<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Merge Two Ailing Guarantee Insurance Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government
Friday announced its decision to merge the country's two ailing
guarantee insurance companies as a further step to clean up the
insurance sector.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Supervisory Commission said it has required the
two insurers -- Korea Guarantee Insurance Co. and Hankuk Fidelity
Surety Co. -- to submit revised restructuring programs outlining
the merger timetable and management replacement, staff and outlet
cuts by next Friday.
</P>
<P>
For the merger, the government will buy the two insurers'
deferred bonds up to 1.6 trillion won (1.2 billion U.S. dollars)
with public funds.
</P>
<P>
The merger is expected to be realized in December this year as
employees must be informed of layoff at least two months in
advance.
</P>
<P>
The two companies are now coordinating their restructuring
plans before submitting a final report to the commission.
</P>
<P>
The commission in charge of financial reforms, which has shut
down 14 merchant banks, five commercial banks and four insurance
companies since the country started suffering the current
financial crisis late last year, is expected to restructure
securities houses, leasing firms and other non-banking
institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
