<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Need More Psychological Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Delegates attending the
ongoing Women's Conference here agreed that more psychological
care should be given to laid-off women since unemployment has been
having a negative affect on women's status in society and the
family.
</P>
<P>
Tan Lin, a scholar with the Tianjin Nankai University, said
unemployment has put great pressure on women, and in some families
has even led to violence against women and children.
</P>
<P>
"Men have become more hot-tempered than before, even though
their wives volunteer to do all the household chores." said Qu
Sufen, vice-chairwoman of the women's federation in east China's
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
A survey in east China's Fujian Province revealed that 23.3
percent of the 120,000 women laid-off there thought their position
in the family had been lowered. At the same time, quarrels between
couples have increased and the divorce rate has risen.
</P>
<P>
Chinese women are most greatly affected during the transition
period, as they represent a considerable proportion of the work
force of reduced sectors such as the textile industry.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, among the 5.77 million registered
laid-off and unemployed workers in China, 52.7 percent were female.
</P>
<P>
"Women feel upset and discouraged when they became unemployed.
The middle-aged especially have a sense of terror about job
hunting and fell great competition if they lack skills," said a
delegate from Tianjin, a major port city in north China.
</P>
<P>
Delegates say they hope the government, organizations and
enterprises can create more jobs for women, provide necessary
psychological counselling, and help them and their families adopt
a positive attitude towards temporary unemployment.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
