<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Reproductive Technology Bill Published in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A bill which provides for
the regulation of reproductive technology in Hong Kong was
gazetted on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Human Reproductive Technology Bill puts in place measures
to ensure that reproductive technology would be safely practiced
and the rights of those involved protected, a government spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
The bill will be introduced to the Legislative Council next
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It provides that a statutory Council on Human Reproductive
Technology be established to be responsible for licensing of
providers of reproductive technology services and persons
conducting embryo research as well as monitoring their compliance
with operational guidelines set out in a code of practice.
</P>
<P>
The bill prohibits sex selection through reproductive
technology for non-medical reasons and commercial surrogacy and
trading in gametes/embryos or fetal ovarian/testicular tissues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
