<HEADLINE> N. Irish Peace "Falling into Place:" Canadian General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian general in charge
of Northern Ireland's decommissioning process, Jean de Chastelain,
said on Friday he believed the peace process "is slowly falling
into place."
</P>
<P>
General Jean de Chastelain, speaking a day after U.S. President
Bill Clinton's visit to the province, said, "I think there is
going to be decommissioning."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Irish News that was published on
Friday, Chastelain said Clinton's trip and the two moves by Sinn
Fein, the Irish Republican Army's political wing, have helped
boost the peace process in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Clinton paid a one-day visit to Northern Ireland on Thursday
and delivered a keynote speech in Belfast, urging people there to
show their courage and reconciliation in the path to peace.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein has recently announced it is time to consign violence
to the history books and appointed a senior party figure to liaise
with the international commission set up to disarm guerrilla
groups.
</P>
<P>
"So far all of the things required in this process and which
people thought might never happen are in fact falling into place
and I think decommissioning is one of them," the disarmament chief
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Northern Ireland peace accord reached last April by
the province's political parties, May 22, 2000, is the final date
for handing in all weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
