<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Depression Unlikely: German Central Bank Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- German central bank president
Hans Tietmeyer has said that he did not expect the financial
crises in Russia and Asia to trigger a global recession, German
media reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to financial journalists Thursday evening in
Frankfurt, Tietmeyer said that despite all the challenges, the
euro zone had retained a "relatively high degree of stability" with
sustained growth clearly under way.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the United States was also continuing despite the
economic problems in other regions, Tietmeyer added.
</P>
<P>
The central bank chief also did not view the big losses on
international stock markets as a crisis symptom, but rather a
signal for corrections of the high rides earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
"I see no worldwide depression in sight at the moment,"
Tietmeyer said.
</P>
<P>
A leading German economic research institute, however, said
Friday that the Russian crisis could trim the German economic
growth this year by about 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Lutz Hoffmann, president of the Berlin-based German Institute
for Economic Research DIW, predicted that the German economy was
likely to grow only by 2.0 percent this year instead of 2.5
percent expected earlier.
</P>
<P>
He also feared that the Russian crisis would effect other
countries in eastern Europe and hold the danger to trigger a
worldwide economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
