<HEADLINE> "The World Becomes One Family" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4, (Xinhua) -- Zubin Mehta, one of the
world's most renouned conductors, will conduct Verdi's Requiem
Mass at the Great Hall of the People on September 13 as part of a
concert titled "The World Becomes One Family." The proceeds from
the concert will all be donated to Chinese flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Zubin Mehta came to China to conduct the opera "Turandot,"
whose heroine is an ancient Chinese princess. Because of the
severe flooding in China this summer, Mr Mehta decided to also
hold this benefit performance as an expression of concern for the
victims and respect for the flood-fighting heroes.
</P>
<P>
According to China's Ministry of Culture, Ministry of Civil
Affairs and the People's Daily, this will be the first benefit
performance by foreign artists since China's floods began in June.
</P>
<P>
This Bombay-born maestro paid his first visit to China in 1992,
and also attended the performance of "1996 Chinese Symphonic Year"
with the Vienna Philharmonic, and today said he will personally
donate 20,000 U.S. dollars and call for more personal donations.
</P>
<P>
The cast of "Turandot" will attend the Great Hall performance
which will also include four world-renouned solo singers from the
Metropolitan, Chicago, and Florence Maggio opera houses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
