<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Bans Ads for 100 Days in Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
barred the newly-appointed ministers from celebrating their one
hundred days in office through paid advertisements on mass media
in a bid to cut expenditures, press reports here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a circular announcing the order in capital Abuja Thursday,
Alhaji Gidado Idris, Secretary to the Federal Government,
requested all ministers, heads of parastatals and government
agencies to take note of this directive and comply with it
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, celebration of 100 days in office by ministers
had always been a media celebration as several organizations buy
newspaper pages and air times in the electronic media to
congratulate those involved.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Office of the Head of State had been
inundated with piles of requests for approval to incur
expenditure on congratulating the Commander-in-Chief on the
occasion of his administration's first 100 days in office.
</P>
<P>
The whole idea was turned down by the government in accordance
with the recommendation of the Program Implementation and
Monitoring Committee, saying it was "too expensive for government
to embark upon at this material time."
</P>
<P>
In the past, several millions of Naira (local currency) had
been lost by the government in such celebrations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
