<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's External Debt Hits 3.6 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- With the rapid development of
its economy, Uganda's external debt burden has hit 3.6 billion
U.S. Dollars, a report by Uganda Debt Network (UDN) has said.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the debt is owed to the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank which insist on servicing the debt
annually, Friday's New Vision daily quoted the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
It says Uganda pays over 140 million Dollars in debt service
each year and each citizen in the country owes more than 180
Dollars to international creditors.
</P>
<P>
UDN has spearheaded the campaign for the international
financial institutions to write off the Uganda debt together with
other Sub-Sahara countries to boost their economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The economies in this region are so depressed and impoverished
that only when they begin to develop can they provide big markets
for the developed economies, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's annual growth rate of Gross Domestic Product has
stood at 6.5 percent over the recent years with more
liberalization of its economy, one of the few success stories on
the African continent which is mostly associated with
backwardness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
