<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Durban Declaration Issued at NAM Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN, South Africa, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The "Durban
Declaration for the New Millennium", issued at the end of the
12th Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) summit, reiterates that the
principles laid down by the founders of NAM remain valid.
</P>
<P>
It also reaffirmed that the ideas and goals articulated then,
continue to guide the Movement.
</P>
<P>
Tested over decades of experience, with a proud history of
achievement and made wiser by the setbacks, the Movement is
emerging "as the power of the new millenn striving to be
open, democratic and a forward-looking group of nations", the
Durban Declaration says.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the international economic situation, it noted
that the twin forces of globalization and liberalization have
resulted in adverse social and economic consequences, which add
to the burdens of everyday life in much of the South.
</P>
<P>
"While globalization holds out the promise of prosperity, it
brings with it severe challenges for the devloping countries,
the declaration added.
</P>
<P>
It called on the NAM countries to take up the challenge to
transform international relations, so as to eradicate aggression,
racism, the use of force, unilateral coercive measures and unfair
economic practices in order to achieve a world of peace, justice
and dignity for all.
</P>
<P>
It also stressed the need to promote South-South cooperation.
"It is a central strategy for creating a new global environment
and speeding up the eradication of poverty," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0180 </DOCNO>
