<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100 People Die of Hunger, Disease in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Hunger and disease have killed
at least 100 people, mostly children, over the past two weeks in
rebel-held Kailahun district of Sierra Leone, health officials in
the eastern part of the country said.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here Friday quoted authorities in Kenema,
240 kilometers east of Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone, as
saying that the deaths from starvation and diarrhoea disease
occurred in the Kailahun district which is a bastion of the
country's rebels.
</P>
<P>
Dominic Ngomsu, an official in the area, said, "it would not
be surprising to learn that children are dying every day in
Kailahun" due to lack of foods and medicines.
</P>
<P>
A non-governmental organization, Christian Relief Services,
has sent foods and medicines into the rebel-held areas in the
country, but aid workers are fearful of setting foot there
because of insecurity.
</P>
<P>
In Sierra Leone, President Ahmad Kabbah returned to power last
March after the west African peace-keeping force ECOMOG ousted a
junta, but renegade soldiers are still creating havoc in
up-country parts of Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
