<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Tumble to Four-year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Australia's wool prices
plunged to a four-year low at this week's sales following the
Australian government's failure to freeze sales of the wool
stockpile during this year.
</P>
<P>
The eastern market indicator slid 26 cents to close at 537
Australian cents a kilogram clean.
</P>
<P>
Exporters attributed the fall to subdued demand.
</P>
<P>
The government tried to freeze the sales last month in a bid to
support weak wool prices but it failed to get the approval
required by law to implement the ban from the parliament since it
was dissolved on August 30 for an October 3 election.
</P>
<P>
But wool broker Wesfarmers Dalgety said resumed sales from the
1.1 million bale stockpile played a role, although to a lesser
degree than the large amount of wool on offer and continuing
subdued world demand for raw wool.
</P>
<P>
About 18 percent of the 89,000 bales of raw wool on offer were
passed in while state-owned Wool International Company sold 9,094
of the 16,000 bales.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Council of Wool Exporters (ACWE) weekly market
review said it remained difficult to predict when a lasting
recovery in demand would happen, due to continued global economic
turbulence.
</P>
<P>
The review said relatively good competition for coarser micron
wool, coupled with continuing interest from China, provided some
encouragement for next week's sales in Sydney and Adelaide where
61,000 bales would be offered.
</P>
<P>
Wesfarmers Dalgety's weekly wool report said increasing
supplies of spring shorn wool would soon enter the market.
</P>
<P>
But it said next week's smaller offering should help support
the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
