<HEADLINE> Israeli Trade Union Threatens to Intensify Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli General Trade Union,
or Histadrut, has threatened to intensify a general strike if the
government continues to reject its demand for a significant wage
hike, Israel Radio reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
After the talks between the Histadrut and the Fiance Ministry
ended in failure Thursday night, Histadrut Chairman Amir Peretz
said he decided to suspend the strike for the weekend to ease the
suffering of the public.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that if the scheduled talks with the Finance
Ministry on Saturday fails again, the strike would continue on
Sunday morning in a full scale.
</P>
<P>
The Histadrut launched the general strike on Thursday in
protest against the low wages of the workers employed in the
public sector.
</P>
<P>
The strike kept 300,000 workers away from their jobs and left
the country in a virtual standstill as all government offices,
post offices, railways, ports and public hospitals were closed.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Federation of Chambers of Commerce estimated that the
strike costs the economy 25 to 30 million shekels (about 6.5 to
7.9 million U.S. dollars) per day.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry had agreed to only 1.25 percent wage hike
for the public sector workers, while the Histadrut is demanding a
8 percent rise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
