<HEADLINE> New Anti-terror Bills Approved in UK, Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Both Britain and the Republic
of Ireland approved new anti-terror laws on Friday following the
terrorist bombing which killed 28 people in the Northern Ireland
town of Omagh last month.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Irish Prime Minister
Bertie Ahern announced the bills in their respective country.
</P>
<P>
The bills will make it easier to convict people of belonging to
outlawed guerrilla groups by giving courts the right to rely on
evidence given by a senior police officer and allowing them to
take an accused person's refusal to answer questions as an
indication of guilt.
</P>
<P>
The Criminal Justice (Terrorism and Conspiracy) Act gained
Royal Assent after clearing all its stages in Britain's House of
Lords in the early hours of Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
In the Irish Republic, similar "draconian" measures became law
with equal haste.
</P>
<P>
The Senate, the upper house of the Irish parliament, approved
the anti-terror bill without a vote on Thursday evening - just
minutes after U.S. President Bill Clinton arrived in Dublin on his
Irish tour. The bill was approved by the Dail, the lower house, a
day earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
