<HEADLINE> Women's Conference Considers Restrictions on Divorce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The revised marriage law
should make people take marriage more seriously and reduce the
number of hasty marriages and divorces, women representatives
attending the ongoing Eighth National Congress of Chinese Women
proposed today.
</P>
<P>
The new code on marriage and the family defines living
separately for three years as a condition for divorce, and
stipulates that married couples must be faithful to each other,
said Wu Changzhen, a female professor of law at the China
University of Political Sciences and Law and one of the authors of
the proposed code.
</P>
<P>
The code should include "mutual faithfulness" as one of the
duties for married couples, which is intended to make extramarital
sexual relations illegal. If one partner has an affair, the other
partner must be compensated if there is a divorce.
</P>
<P>
"Most complaints from women involve extra-marital affairs, and
the revision of the Marriage Law should put severe restrictions on
the subject," said Li Li, vice-chairperson of the Shanghai
Municipal Women's Federation. She said family stability and
happiness should be sought through comprehensive means instead of
solely by legal efforts.
</P>
<P>
Chinese have little self-protection awareness, and sexually
related diseases could run rampant if extramarital sex is not
checked, said Lin Huizhu, vice-chairperson of the Guangdong
Women's Federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
