<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin: Russia to Enter "Economic Dictatorship" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin said here Friday that Russia "will switch over to
economic dictatorship" from January.
</P>
<P>
"I am prepared to shoulder the responsibility for the
realization of this course," he told the Federation Council, or
upper house of parliament, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin asked the Federation Council to support him and
give its consent to urgent actions of the government.
</P>
<P>
"At my age of 60 there is no need for me to bluff. I fully
realize the degree of responsibility," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is true that our measures will be unpopular. It is true
that everybody, from top to bottom, will scold us. But do not
catch the government by the hands," Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, nominated prime minister last week, was rejected
overwhelmingly on Monday by the State Duma, or lower house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
"Give us time, give us a chance to start working," he said.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma is set to debate and vote on Chernomyrdin's
nomination later Friday. Many opposition parties have indicated
they will vote against him.
</P>
<P>
Under Russian constitution, if the State Duma blocks the
nomination three times, the president will have to either submit a
new nominee or dissolve the lower house.
</P>
<P>
"I am telling everybody, including the president and the
legislative branch: let the country retreat from the edge of the
abyss."
</P>
<P>
As the political haggling goes on in Moscow, Russia's economic
and financial crisis worsened.
</P>
<P>
On the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange, the ruble was traded
at 16.99 to one U.S. dollar on Friday, a fall of some 170 percent
as compared to the pre-crisis level.
</P>
<P>
Prices soared and some staple food products are vanishing from
the shelves of grocery stores amid reports of poor harvest and
looming food shortages.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin warned that if panic is not stopped in the next
few days and stocks of materials and food are not gathered for the
winter, the country could slip back to the miserable situation
prevailing at the end of 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
