<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Names Head of China Research Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Intel, the world's largest
chip maker, named Dr. Robert Yung, a former Sun Microsystems
researcher, head of the newly-established Intel China Research
Center on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Intel has planned to invest 50 million U.S. dollars during the
next five years in the center, which will focus on research on
applied technology.
</P>
<P>
Intel's worldwide research and development effort during the
next five years will cost 2.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"China is a big and fast-growing market with a rich supply of
well-trained scientists and engineers. The Chinese language also
poses special challenges in computing, and we're looking forward
to doing some research that will benefit both China and other
countries as well." Yung, a 36 Chinese-American, said in a
telephone interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, Yung said, he met many smart, talented
and well-informed people in China's academia and business
community as well as in the government.
</P>
<P>
"That's one of the reasons I want to go to China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yung said that the center will fund projects at China's leading
universities and research institutes as well as conducting its own
research.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to work very closely with the nation's academic
community," he said.
</P>
<P>
Immediately prior to joining Intel, Yung was Sun Microsystems'
chief technology officer for the Asia region and was a researcher
at Sun Microsystems' Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
He immigrated from Hong Kong to the United States when he was
11. He earned his Ph.D. in electrical engineering and computer
science from the University of California at Berkeley, and has
been a visiting professor at the university since 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
