<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeological Finds Provide Evidence for Dating Ancient Dynasties (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A group of leading
archeologists recently came upon several cultural sites and relics
dating back as far as 4,000 years ago. These finds may possibly
provide evidence for precise dating of the first three dynasties
in China.
</P>
<P>
The Institute of Archeology under the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences (CASS) did excavations at the Erlitou sites and the
ancient town of the Shang Dynasty, both in Yanshi in central Henan
Province, another ancient town ruins of the late Shang Dynasty,
and the Fenghao ruins in Xi'an in northwestern Shaanxi Province,
Miao Yajuan told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
"The latest archeological finds have made great contributions
to the nation's endeavor to unravel the complete chronology of its
5,000-year history," she said.
</P>
<P>
A research project has been organized to determine precise
dates for the Xia (21th-16th Century BC), Shang (16th to 11th
Century BC) Zhou (11th Century-226 BC) dynasties which have
inspired many legends and anecdotes. The major study focuses on
events some 2,800 to 4,000 years ago to gain accurately
apportioned time-frames for the three dynasties.
</P>
<P>
The existing historical chronicles for China, one of the
world's four ancient civilizations, begins in 841 B.C., so there
is no precise record for nearly half of the nation's remote
history.
</P>
<P>
"The Erlitou sites are always principal research targets for
tracing cultural development in the Xia Dynasty (22th-17th century
B.C.)," Miao said.
</P>
<P>
After 30 years of excavations at these sites totalling about
three sq km, researchers spotted traces of the ruins of two
palaces, workshops for manufacturing bone tools, sacrificial
places and hundreds of tombs, and unearthed bronzes, jade objects,
lacquerware and other relics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeological Finds Provide Evidence for Dating Ancient Dynasties (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the same sites they found a series of cultural layers at the
first to fifth stages of development.
</P>
<P>
In addition, archeologists found the city wall, city gates and
palaces inside the city, and residential houses at the ruins of
the Shang Dynasty town (17th-11th century B.C.), five kilometers
from Erlitou.
</P>
<P>
They also found an inner town, 1,100 meters by 740 meters,
inside the previously discovered town. "Study shows that the inner
city was built much earlier than the large one," Miao said.
</P>
<P>
Thus, experts have ascertained that the town was the capital of the
early Shang Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
At the ruins of Yinxu in the city of Anyang, Henan Province,
which was regarded the capital of the late Shang Dynasty, experts
unearthed a great number of cultural relics, giving them greater
knowledge of the scale, layout and cultural stages of the ancient
town.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, some prime samples dating from the reigns of King Wu
of the Shang Dynasty and other kings of the Western Zhou Dynasty
(B.C.11th Century-771 B.C.) were collected at the Fenghao ruins in
Shaanxi.  
</P>
