<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO to Hold Joint Exercise in Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- NATO will exercise its
infantry together with its equivalent from Partnership for Peace
nations in Macedonia from September 10 to 18.
</P>
<P>
The joint military exercise, named Cooperative Best Effort 98
and drawn participation from 26 countries, will be held at
Krivolak, a permanent training center for NATO's Partnership for
Peace (PFP) program.
</P>
<P>
The exercise aims at coordinating troops from different
countries in a typical peacekeeping scenario and focuses on
fostering mutual understanding and improving interoperability.
</P>
<P>
NATO officials said that the Macedonia exercise would also
demonstrate the important contribution NATO's PFP can make to the
fostering of stability and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
Fixed-wing NATO aircraft will fly by Krivolak to demonstrate an
air-borne parachute drop during the exercise.
</P>
<P>
Those already confirmed participation include, on the NATO
side, Canada, Denmark, France, Germany, Greece, Italy, the
Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Spain, Turkey, Britain and the
United States; and on the PFP nation side, Albania, Austria,
Azerbaijan, Bulgaria, Estonia, Macedonia, Georgia, Hungary,
Latvia, Moldova, Poland, Romania and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Finland, though not participating, will provide the exercise
with technical support.
</P>
<P>
NATO held a joint exercise in mid-August in neighboring Albania
to demonstrate the western military alliance's concern over the
crisis in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo and its readiness to
deploy what it describes as a preventive troop to the region to
fend off the possible spillover of the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
