<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army to Kill Aggressors: General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Uganda People's Defense
Forces (UPDF) will kill all those threatening the country's
security on its western border, a major general has said Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Salim Saleh, President Yoweri Museveni's brother and the
presidential adviser on military affairs, made the remarks from
his headquarters in northern Gulu district.
</P>
<P>
He warned Zimbabwean and Angolan troops in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) that they will meet a tough response from
Ugandan army if they pose any threat to Uganda's security,
Friday's Monitor daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Salim described the threats by Zimbabwean commander Mike
Nyambuya of looking forward to an eastern offensive as a move
aimed to cover the failures the allied forces had suffered along
the western front-line.
</P>
<P>
In a few days, these Angolan and Zimbabweans will realize that
they have involved themselves in a situation they cannot easily
walk away from, he added.
</P>
<P>
But he reportedly shunned the question of whether Ugandan army
still remains deep in Congo (K) as he confessed last week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Y. Museveni said in a press release
Thursday that his country could conditionally discuss Ugandan
military presence in Congo with parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
This move was made in response to the sharp turn of attitude
by South Africa toward the Congo conflict and to some other
countries in the Southern African Development Community who have
come to side with President Laurent Kabila by supporting foreign
military intervention. 
</P>
