<HEADLINE> Iraqi Kurdish Faction Complains About Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Kurdistan Democratic
Party (KDP) leader Massoud Barzani has complained about Iranian
interference in northern Iraq, local Daily News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Barzani lodged his complaint in meetings with western diplomats
in Ankara, which was particularly directed at the Iranian
influence on KDP's rival Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) led by
Jalal Talabani.
</P>
<P>
Barzani, who arrived here Wednesday night for a four-day
visit, will travel to Washington on Saturday to discuss creating
a joint administration in northern Iraq with Talabani under the
mediation of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The KDP and PUK have been fighting for the control of northern
Iraq since 1991 Gulf War after the region became a power vacuum.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the western diplomats who met with Barzani
as saying that the KDP leader also complained about the PUK
support for the outlawed anti-Turkish Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK)
in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Barzani seemed to be satisfied with the cooperation with
Turkey in fighting against the PKK, the diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
KDP Spokesman Sami Abdurrahman said Thursday here that the
basic dispute between the KDP and PUK is the sharing of the
administration.
</P>
<P>
"We wanted the joint administration in 1992, but the PUK
defended the view that the administration has to be shared equally
between the two sides", he said.
</P>
<P>
The KDP controls two-thirds of the Kurdish-controlled area in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In March, Talabani sent a letter to Barzani seeking a broad
reconciliation with the KDP in a bid to set up a permanent peace
in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Talabani proposed a high-level meeting between
the two factions to sort out their differences. 
</P>
