<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty, Not Immigrants, To Blame for TB: NZ Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Dominion newspaper
Friday quoted an Auckland medical expert as saying that poverty,
not immigrants, is to blame for an outbreak of tuberculosis in New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Since December, seven students at Tangaroa College in Otara,
South Auckland, have been diagnosed with tuberculosis and a
further five students have the infection in the first mass
outbreak of tuberculosis in New Zealand in a decade.
</P>
<P>
This week, an immigrant pupil at Mt Roskill Intermediate in
Auckland was also diagnosed with the illness.
</P>
<P>
Mass tuberculosis screenings are being done in parts of the
North Island, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Some health authorities, including the Communicable Disease
Center and Auckland medical officer of health Lester Calder, have
blamed emigration from the Pacific and Asia for the prevalence of
tuberculosis in New Zealand, sparking calls for all immigrants to
be screened for the disease.
</P>
<P>
But the Dominion quoted Dr Colin Tukuitonga, senior lecturer at
Auckland University school of medicine, as saying that it was "a
Load of rot" to blame Pacific and Asian immigrants for
tuberculosis in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Dr Tukuitonga said the real cause of tuberculosis was poverty.
Conditions contributing to the spread of the disease, such as
overcrowded housing, poor nutrition and general health, and lack
of access to health care, were rife in some New Zealand
communities, particularly in urban South Auckland.
</P>
<P>
"It's a load of rot to say it is imported, when the problem is
here in New Zealand," he said.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Minister of Immigration Tuariki Delamere was quoted
as saying that he did not support calls for the screening of
immigrants for the disease.
</P>
<P>
Figures issued by the New Zealand Ministry of Health show that
last year 330 cases of tuberculosis were recorded in the country,
compared to 355 in 1996 and 375 in 1995. The figures were well
down on recent decades. In 1960, 1,400 cases were notified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
