<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Lebanese Militia Chief Frees Woman Assassin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese woman who attempted
to kill the leader of the Israeli allied South Lebanese Army (SLA)
Antoine Lahd has been released, the Daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Suha Beshara, 31, was driven by the International Committee of
the Red Cross to Beirut Thursday via the Bater crossing, north of
the country's central area of Jezzine controlled by SLA.
</P>
<P>
She received a hero's welcome by her family, friends and
Lebanese officials, including Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri.
</P>
<P>
Her release was reportedly secured after Hariri sought the
help of French President Jacques Chirac who threatened to revoke
the French citizenship of Lahd if he didn't free Beshara.
</P>
<P>
Lahd's family is living in France and he is expected to
move there once Israel withdraws from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon backed by the Lahd-led SLA to allegedly protect
its north from cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Lahd, 68, has been sentenced to death in absentia by a
Beirut military court for collaborating with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Having befriended Lahd's wife and become a tutor to her
children, Beshara, a secret member of the Lebanese Communist
Party, made the assassination attempt on Lahd on November 7,
1988.
</P>
<P>
Lahd was wounded in the arm and shoulder and Beshara was
detained at the SLA prison at Khiam village in the south.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference after being released, Beshara said she had
no regret for what she had done. And she vowed to continue her
struggle until her country was fully liberated from Israeli
occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
