<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Turn One-Million Lumberjacks Into Tree Planters (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- China plans to begin a
gigantic forest-conservation project this year which is expected
to turn one-million-odd lumberjacks into tree planters.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, the first-phase of the project, from
1998 to 2000, will require 19.5 billion yuan (about 2.3 billion
U.S. dollars) of investment.
</P>
<P>
This project was adopted by the State Forestry Administration
and includes the stopping of logging operations of 65 lumber
businesses and reducing the lumber production of another 70 lumber
businesses by 10 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from forestry departments indicate that with the
implementation of this forest-conservation project, over one
million people now employed by the forestry industry will lose
their present jobs by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Li Yucai, Deputy Director of the State Forestry Administration,
said most of those laid-off will have new jobs as tree planting,
forest-tenders, and other related work.
</P>
<P>
He said Heilongjiang, Jilin and Sichuan provinces, which have
vast primitive forests, have made preparations for the start of
the biggest forest-conservation project in China this century.
</P>
<P>
Li added that the central government has provided over 6
billion yuan (about 723 million U.S. dollars) in addition to
special funds for the project this year.
</P>
<P>
"This unprecedented largest sum of investment for forestry
since the founding of New China indicates the central
government is determined to protect the forests," Li said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Discovers Large Coal Gas Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- China recently discovered a
huge coal gas field in northern Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The field, located near the cities of Jincheng and Changzhi in
southeast Shanxi, has an area of more than 1,200 square kilometers
and proven gas reserves of more than 200 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The discovery came after more than two years of geological
exploration. Experts say that the field can generate up to one
billion cubic meters of coal gas each year, and that this amount
is large enough to meet the industrial and civilian needs of the
major cities in southeast Shanxi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Turn One-Million Lumberjacks Into Tree Planters (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li said that when the second phase of the project is completed
in 2010, China's forests will be better protected and lumber
production will rely mainly on the newly planted forests.
</P>
<P>
China has 87.26 million hectares of forests, accounting for 9
percent of its land territory.
</P>
<P>
One forestry expert warns that if logging continues at the
present rate, the Chinese people will not see a single forest
left in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that this project will benefit 61 percent of
China's major forests.
</P>
<P>
Forestry experts have also called for state-level protection of
the other 39 percent of the forests under the administration of
local governments.
</P>
<P>
Experts have stressed the importance of forests in retaining
water resources, maintaining ecological balance, and reducing soil
erosion.
</P>
<P>
They say that a huge tree can store 4 tons of water, while the
logging of one cu. m. of lumber will add 0.4 tons of silt to
a river annually.
</P>
<P>
The State Forestry Administration believes that the devastating
floods in China this summer are due, at least in part, to
deforestation and the serious damage it has done to vegetation
along the upper reaches of the Yangtze and other rivers.
</P>
<P>
He announced that China will impose a forest-logging ban in the
Yangtze and Yellow rivers valley areas and focus on planting more
trees in farmlands where forests have formerly flourished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
