<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists: Fish Oil May Reduce Psychiatric Disorders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Three scientists reported
their studies Thursday that the consumption of fish and fish oil
may reduce the symptoms of variety of psychiatric illnesses,
including schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, and depression.
</P>
<P>
The studies were released at a seminar sponsored by the
National Institutes of Health in Bethesds, Maryland.
</P>
<P>
The first study, conducted by Dr. Andrew Stoll of the Harvard
Medical School in Massachusetts, found that fish oil
supplementation could help alleviate the symptoms of bipolar
(manic-depressive) disorder.
</P>
<P>
Stoll said he gave 14 bipolar patients daily supplements of
fish oil for a 4-month period, 9 of the patients responded
favorably, compared to only 3 of 16 bipolar patients receiving
placebo.
</P>
<P>
The second study, conducted by Dr. Malcolm Peet of Northern
General Hospital in England, concluded that, following 3-month
period, fish oil improved patients with schizophrenic symptoms.
</P>
<P>
The third study, conducted by Dr. Joseph Hibblen of the
National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism in Maryland,
said that some suicidal patients may reduce their suicidal risk
with the consumption of fish oil.
</P>
<P>
Hibblen explained that dietary intake of omega-3 fatty acids,
found in fish and fish oil, may influence serotonin function in
the brain.
</P>
<P>
"Such an alteration in serotoninergic function may possibly
reduce depressive, suicidal and violent behavior," he said, but
admitting that these changes have not yet been demonstrated in
clinical trials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0232 </DOCNO>
