<HEADLINE> Zambian Gay Promoters Face Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
instructed law enforcement officers to arrest anybody
spearheading registration of an association for the country's
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs Minister Peter Machungwa, warned in Lusaka
Thursday that police would arrest leaders of the group if they
tried to register it, government-owned Zambia Daily Mail said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Machungwa noted that the Zambian government would not promote
lawlessness in the nation and urged leaders of the group to come
down to earth.
</P>
<P>
Machungwa came out in support of earlier warnings from Legal
Affairs Minister Vincent Malambo and Dav{D$Mpamba, Minister of
Information and Broadcasting Services. Both of them warned last
Monday that the government would not permit homosexual activities
because they were illegal and an abomination of African culture.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Beenwell Chimfwembe also warned those who
advocated the existence of an association for gay people risked
facing the law.
</P>
<P>
Registrar of Societies Herbert Nyendwa said in Lusaka on the
same day that he would not register anybody wishing to form an
association for homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
He explained that his organization could not register any
association for homosexuals because the activity was illegal.
</P>
<P>
Independent newspaper The Post Thursday quoted Alfred Zulu,
the project coordinator for the country's gay movement and
president of Zambia Independent Monitoring Team, as saying that
there were about 500,000 gays throughout Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Zulu even urged the government to "copy the example of South
Africa which has legalized homosexuality and incorporated it in
the Republican Constitution". 
</P>
</TEXT>
