<HEADLINE> NBA Arbitration Hearing Reopen Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The NBA arbitration
hearing opened again Thursday with only the executive director
and an associate counsel of the NBA players union witnessed the
12-hours testimony in New York.
</P>
<P>
The hearing is about the issue over whether players with
guaranteed contracts should be paid during the lockout by owners.
</P>
<P>
The hearing before arbitrator John Feerick began at 9 a.m.
with associate counsel Ron Klempner on the stand and it
councluded at 9 p.m. with union director Billy Hunter testifying.
</P>
<P>
Hunter is scheduled to resume his testimony Friday morning.
The hearing is scheduled to end Tuesday. Post-hearing briefs must
be filed by September 15, and Feerick will then have 30 days to
render his verdict.
</P>
<P>
The lockout has been in effect for two months but the two
sides only met once formally. That session ended abruptly when
the owners walked out of the room upon hearing the players'
latest proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
