<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras, Hingis Advances to Third Round at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Pete Sampras of
the United States continued his quest for a record-tying 12th
Grand Slam title later today when he eliminated unseeded
countryman Paul Goldstein 7-6 (7-4), 2-6, 6-3, 6-3 in the second
round of the U.S. Open tennis championships in New York.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, top seed and defending champion Martina Hingis of
Switzerland survived a shaky first set to beat 1997 French Open
champion Iva Majoli of Croatia in the second round.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who is also looking to finish as the top-ranked
player a record sixth straight year, found Goldstein was a hard
nut to crack today. Goldstein, who won his first Grand Slam match
Monday, took advantage of several unforced errors by Sampras to
force a tie-breaker. But Sampras rode his big serve for a 5-0
lead and won the set when Goldstein's forehand sailed long.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Goldstein rebounded in the second set,
breaking Sampras in the fourth game. He took a 5-2 advantage when
Sampras double-faulted, his second of the game.
</P>
<P>
However, Sampras found his composure and dominated the rest of
the match, claiming third-set service breaks in the seventh and
ninth games. He closed out the match in two hours, eight minutes
when Goldstein's forehand landed wide.
</P>
<P>
Sampras fired 23 aces but committed 10 double-faults. His
first serve was practically untouchable as he won the point 91
percent of the time. He made 43 unforced errors through the first
two set, but just 14 thereafter.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Greg Rusedski of Britain, who was beaten by Rafter
in last year's final, won his second straight five-set match 4-6,
6-3, 4-6, 6-2, 7-5 today over Bohdan Ulihrach of the Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
"I was thinking about joining the women's tour," joked
Rusedski. "You only have to play three sets, maximum. But a win
is a win. I knew I had a difficult match today."
</P>
<P>
Hingis was pushed to a first-set tie-breaker before responding
with a 7-6 (7-4), 6-0 victory over the unseeded Majoli. "I didn't
feel like I controlled the game," said Hingis, who has won six of
eight career matches from Majoli. "I was just very nervous the
first set. I was still also in the second. I kind of loosened up
and everything started to go in."
</P>
<P>
The Swiss teenager broke Majoli's serve in the fourth game of
the first set but the 20-year-old Croatian broke back three games
later. Both players held serve as the set went to tiebreaker,
which Hingis won when Majoli's forehand went outside.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't let her back in the game," Hingis said. "I was
focused from the first game on."
</P>
<P>
In a first round match that began yesterday but was postponed
by rain, seventh seed Alex Corretja of Spain rallied past Italy's
Gianluca Pozzi 2-6, 6-3, 7-5, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
Eighth seed Andre Agassi of the United States won his first
five-setter of the year 6-3, 6-2, 6-7 (6-8), 3-6, 6-1 over
tenacious Frenchman Guillaume Raoux.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, who improved to 42-11 at the U.S. Open, fell to
Alberto Berasategui at the Australian Open and 18-year-old
Russian Marat Safin at the French Open in his previous five-set
matches.
</P>
<P>
"I was really frustrated with myself for letting it get to the
fourth," Agassi said. "You can't affort to have that happen. But
I don't mind it being this way. It wasn't tremendously fatiguing
match, which normally five-setters. You worry about just playing
too much. I think it was certainly a wake-up call of sort for me
to be up two sets and not to close it out and find myself in a
three-hour battle."
</P>
<P>
No.9 Karol Kucera of Slovakia downed France's Jerome Golmard
7-5, 6-3, 6-0 and No.12 Jonas Bjorkman of Sweden posted an easy
6-2, 6-3, 6-1 win over American Jonathan Stark.
</P>
<P>
On the women's side, second seed Lindsay Davenport of the
United States cruised past countrywoman Lori McNeil 6-1, 6-1.
Fourth seed and 1994 winner Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain
defeated Colombian Fabiola Zuluaga 6-3, 6-2 and 1997 runner-up
Venus Williams of the United States, the fifth seed, dispatched
Luxembourg's Anne Kremer 6-1, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed Conchita Martinez of Spain beat American
Jacqueline Trail 7-6 (7-4), 6-1; No.10 Nathalie Tauziat of
France, the Wimbledon finalist, overcame Olga Barabanschikova of
Belarus 6-7 (4-7), 6-2, 6-3; No.12 seed Mary Pierce of France
eliminated Zimbabwe's Cara Black 6-1, 6-1. No.13 seed Amanda
Coetzer of South Africa beat Raluca Sandu of Romania 6-0, 6-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
