<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 September 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA -- More than 60 percent of foreign investors are
satisfied with the financial environment in Bulgaria, according to
a survey conducted by the Bulgarian Telegraph Agency.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors showed the most interest in tourism,
agriculture, light industry and telecommunications, while listing
high standards education, low labor costs and the proximity to
large neighboring markets as reasons to come to Bulgaria. But they
complained about certain laws and regulations, the inefficiency of
official institutions, out-of-date infrastructure, relatively high
taxes, and the poor local market. (Bulgarian-Survey-Foreign
Investment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil's exports to the Latin American
Integration Association (Aladi) countries increased by 14 percent
from January to July.
</P>
<P>
Exports totaled 8.14 billion U.S. dollars, compared to 7.14
billion dollars in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports during that period reached 7.4 billion dollars, 297
million dollars less than in 1997. (Brazil-Export)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- Inflation in August, the first month for Ecuador's new
government, was 1.3 percent, slightly higher than July's rate, but
equal to that of August, 1997.
</P>
<P>
This year's accumulated inflation amounts to 24.7 percent,
while the annual inflation, from August of 1997 to August of 1998
reached 34.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economic authorities forecast that the annual inflation would
be 40 percent. (Ecuador-Inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The 12th Summit of the Group of Rio will give
preference in its working agenda to the sustained development of
Latin America, Adan Castillo Galastica, Panama's Livestock
Development Ministry spokesman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Castillo, who is attending this international event as an
observer, highlighted the need for promoting the socio-economic
development of Latin America, which is being hit by a serious
financial crisis because of the situations in Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting of the Latin American presidents, members of the
Group of Rio, will have a positive effect on the regional
economy," he said. (Rio Summit-Development)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Eleven American nations vowed on Thursday to
promote "sustained growth" through sound fiscal policies in a bid
to ward off the economic crises enveloping Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
In a communique after the first day of their meeting, finance
officials from nine Latin American countries, Canada and the U.S.
said they would pursue "continued macroeconomic stability" and
implement "sound fiscal policies" in order to gain economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The countries -- including Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Colombia,
Ecuador, Mexico, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela -- would also
maintain their current exchange rate policies and regimes, open
capital markets and continue their structural reforms.  (Western
Hemisphere-Growth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's exports amounted to 8.909 billion
U.S. dollars during the first seven months of 1998, a 12.7 percent
drop compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Affairs Ministry's Exports Promotion Direction said
that the biggest drop was registered in the sales to Asia, with a
reduction of 36.1 percent, totaling 2.315 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The only Asian nation where Chilean exports continued growing
was China which had imports valued at 241 million dollars, a 42.1
percent increase. (Chile-Export Drop) 
</P>
</TEXT>
