<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Strives for Effective Forest Conservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yangon, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has been striving for
effective forest conservation to maintain sustainable yield of
forest products by extending reserved forest area and carrying out
natural forest regeneration and artificial forest plantation.
</P>
<P>
The country's total reserved forest area was extended to
106,288 square kilometers (sq.-km) in March, the end of 1997-98
fiscal year, increasing by 2,333 sq.-km at the same period of the
previous year, according to a latest annual official report on
the country's forestry condition.
</P>
<P>
During the fiscal year, area under natural regeneration for
valuable tree species was extended by 8,748 hectares, while that
under artificial forest plantation expanded by 33,987 hectares,
on which plantation of 1.26 million teak trees and 2.52 million
hardwood trees were carried out.
</P>
<P>
The plantation of the two main kinds of trees added up to 29.16
million and 39.7 million respectively at the end of the fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
Other 11.3 million saplings were also planted by the public
during the year.
</P>
<P>
For systematic conservation of forest in the country's arid
zone, the State Forestry Department has been implementing since
the 1992-93 a greening and environmental control project in 13
districts of the zone constituted with three central divisions of
Mandalay, Sagaing and Magway.
</P>
<P>
The projects include the establishment of nurseries,
conservation of remaining natural forest from further
deterioration, replacement of fuel wood, restoration of watershed
areas and establishment of water resources.
</P>
<P>
The project covers a total area of 9,142,380 hectares. Of
these, 1,529,879 hectares are reserved forest, 3,281,135 hectares
land outside them and 4,331,366 hectares cropping areas.
</P>
<P>
In addition to these, Myanmar also carried out protection of
wild life and wild plants and conservation of natural area,
establishing seven natural and wildlife sanctuaries and six
national parks.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has begun implementation of another 12-year greening
project from 1997-98 to 2008-09.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar promulgated the Forest Law in 1992 to effectively
conserve and preserve the forest which covers about 51 percent of
the total land area.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, Myanmar's forestry rose 1.3
percent in its production in the 1997-98, accounting for 1 percent
of the country's gross domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
