<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mother May Pass Lead to Baby Through Breast Milk: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Women who have been
exposed to high lead levels may pass the substance to their
infants through breast milk, according to a study released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The study, funded by the U.S. National Institute of
Environmental Health Sciences, said lead can accumulate in bones
and may be released into the blood when bone minerals tend to
mobilize to ensure an adequate calcium supply in breast milk.
</P>
<P>
Breast milk is considered the best infant nutrition and will
only contain lead if the mother's "exposures are very high, such
as around smelters, house renovations with leaded paint, dietary
sources from lead-glazed pottery, cosmetics and traditional
medicine", said Dr Brian Gulson, an Australian scientist who
helped conduct the study.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four Australian infants and 21 mothers, including 15
immigrant women, took part in the study.
</P>
<P>
"We have found that breast milk was responsible for about 36 to
80 percent of the lead in the infants' bodies in the first 60 to
90 days after birth," the researchers said, suggesting that it
would be worthwhile to measure lead concentration in breast milk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador's Inflation Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Inflation in August, the first
month for Ecuador's new government, was 1.3 percent, says the
Ecuador Statistics and Census Institute (INEC).
</P>
<P>
It was slightly higher than July's inflation, but equal to that
of August, 1997.
</P>
<P>
This year's accumulated inflation amounts to 24.7 percent,
while the annual inflation, from August of 1997 to August of 1998
reached 34.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economic authorities forecast that the annual inflation would
be 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, inflation will depend on measures adopted by the
government of President Jamil Mahuad. Investors are waiting for
the government's economic plan to decide on their investments.
</P>
<P>
Figures from INEC show prices of 163 items rose in August,
including food, house rents, medicines and water.
</P>
<P>
The local press expects September's inflation to be very high
because of the payment of school fees to various education
centers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
