<HEADLINE> Brazil's Exports to Aladi Countries Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's exports to the
Latin American Integration Association (Aladi) countries increased
by 14 percent from January to July.
</P>
<P>
Exports totalled 8.14 billion U.S. dollars, compared to 7.14
billion dollars in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports during that period reached 7.4 billion dollars, 297
million dollars less than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Brazil had a 742-million-dollar trade surplus with the Aladi
countries from January to July, and a trade deficit of 524 million
dollars in its transaction with the Aladi countries in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Aladi countries, importing 26.3 percent of Brazil's total
exports this year, are the second biggest market for Brazil's
products, while the European Union, which buys 29 percent of
Brazilian exports, is the biggest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
