<HEADLINE> Thai Rice Exporters to Negotiate with Malaysia Buyers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Thai rice exporters are to
negotiate with Malaysian buyers over the settlement of previous
deals following the adoption of fixed ringgit exchange rate, a
source from Thai Rice Exporters Association told Xinhua Friday.
</P>
<P>
The source said the date for talks is yet to be set.
</P>
<P>
Exporters are now closely monitoring the situation to avoid
increased risks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thai rice markets was nervous after its third-largest rice
buyer, Malaysia, set controls on the ringgit and exporters
pondered the fate of unsettled deals.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia imports 400,000 to 500,000 tons of high quality rice,
fragrant rice and 100-percent white rice worth over 4.5 billion
U.S. dollars from Thailand each year.
</P>
<P>
The export volume reached 250,000 tons worth 3.75 billion baht
(93.75 million dollars) during the first seven months of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Payments between the two neighbors have traditionally been in
three currencies: baht, U.S. dollar and ringgit.
</P>
<P>
With ringgit set to lose its value outside Malaysia from
October 1, it was unclear what currency Malaysia planned to use in
settling previous deals and at what rate.
</P>
<P>
However, the source said the Thai rice exports will not be
seriously affected by the Malaysian currency policy since rice is
one of the most important foodstuffs of the Malaysian people.
</P>
</TEXT>
