<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Set Up Community Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's council of social
ministers have approved to set up a fund worth 21.7 billion baht
(542 million U.S. dollars) to finance social investment projects
for communities nationwide, the Nation newspaper said Friday,
quoting Prime Minister's Office Minister Supatra Masdit.
</P>
<P>
Supatra said the fund, aiming to create a substantial
self-dependent economy for communities, will be set up with a soft
loan of 21.7 billion baht from the World Bank and will be
distributed to communities for two years.
</P>
<P>
Communities and community-based organizations, which had been
continually carrying out activities in the interest of the
communities, would be eligible to seek support from the so-called
"Community Fund".
</P>
<P>
The Government Savings Bank will cooperate with the Finance
Ministry in granting financial support to the communities.
</P>
<P>
"The fund will help create jobs and provide chances for
communities to earn more," the minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Projects qualified for receiving support would include those
promoting tourism.
</P>
<P>
She said the community organizations would have to shoulder ten
percent of the cost of the projects while the fund would make a 90
percent contribution. 
</P>
