<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Survivors Found in Swiss Plane Crash Off Canadian Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Almost 24 hours after the
tragic crash of Swissair Flight 111 off Canada's east coast, no
survivors have been found of the 229 passengers and crew aboard,
and there has been no word about what caused the catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports said that about 44 bodies had been recovered
from the Atlantic sea off Peggy's Cove, a tiny fishing village on
the south shore of Canada's Nova Scotia province.
</P>
<P>
Though it seemed almost impossible to find any survivors,
Canadian searchers were still looking for miracles, hoping that
some would survive the huge impact of the crash and cold waters.
</P>
<P>
Swissair said there were no survivors from the crash. "We have
to suppose that there are no survivors," said Philippe Bruggisser,
chief executive officer of the Geneva-based airline.
</P>
<P>
Of the 215 passengers and 14 crew aboard the jet, there were
136 Americans, 39 Swiss nationals, 30 French citizens, and people
from Britain, Canada, Germany, Italy, Greece, Saudi Arabia,
Yugoslavia, Afghanistan, Iran, Spain, St. Kitts and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The three-engine plane, enroute from New York to Geneva,
reported smoke in the cockpit after a normal takeoff from JFK
international airport about 8:18 p.m. EDT Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The crew decided to turn back to Boston. After being told that
the Halifax airport was closer, the plane flew in the direction of
Halifax.
</P>
<P>
The wide-bodied MD-11 jet crashed about 10:30 p.m. local time,
(0130 GMT) Wednesday into the ocean several kilometers from
Peggy's Cove, about 60 kilometers short of the Halifax airport.
</P>
<P>
Roy Bears of Canada's Transportation Safety Board said early
indications are that the Swissair crash was not the result of a
terrorist act.
</P>
<P>
"There were 16 minutes elapsed from the time they initially
declared an urgent situation -- smoke in the cockpit" to the time
the plane disappeared from radar.
</P>
<P>
"At this point...the crew don't think they have anything that
would indicate a terrorist act," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Canadian military aircraft, coast guard vessels and fishing
boats scoured the crash waters through the night and day.
</P>
<P>
The inky and rough water made it difficult for rescue people
navigate through the debris field, which spread a couple of
kilometers across the sea.
</P>
<P>
"When you saw how small the pieces of fragments were, you could
tell it must have been a pretty horrific crash," said Jim Buckley,
a fishing boat skipper.
</P>
<P>
Almost 24 hours after the crash, about 44 bodies, some only
body parts, had been recovered from the choppy waters, Canadian
police said.
</P>
<P>
The bodies were taken to a temporary morgue at the Canadian
Forces Base Shearwater. Dozens of doctors, including dentists and
pathologists, worked to identify remains.
</P>
<P>
So far, only small pieces of debris have been brought ashore. A
chunk of the plane's fuselage is reported to have been located on
the ocean floor.
</P>
<P>
Divers will be used to try and recover the plane's flight
recorders, which could help determine the cause of the
disaster. Waters in the area are about 50 meters deep.
</P>
<P>
Police appealed to the public Thursday to turn in any debris
from the crash which might wash ashore.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the Swiss were reported to have sent
teams of experts to the crash site to help the
investigation. McDonnell Boeing, the makers of the jet, also sent
a team of people to Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
Swissair and its partner, Delta Airlines, were flying victims'
relatives to Halifax, where about 900 hotel rooms have been booked
for the families.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien expressed
his sadness at the crash.
</P>
<P>
"The families and loved ones of those who have been lost in
this terrible disaster are in all of our thoughts and prayers,"
Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister pledged that Canada would do everything it
could to conduct the recovery and investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
