<TEXT>
<P>
Yangon, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar Industrial
Development Bank (MIDB), a state-private capitalized financial
institution, is planning to open its more branches in industrial
zones in the country to widely disburse loans to local industries
as a support to them for their engagements.
</P>
<P>
The MIDB, established in February 1996 involving shares of
government and private sector, has recently opened its first
branch bank in the Meiktila Industrial Zone in central part, one
of the 17 in the country.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Minister of Industry Major-General Hla Myint Swe was
quoted by Friday's The New Light of Myanmar newspaper as saying
that the bank has raised the interest rate by 15 percent to
attract more savings.
</P>
<P>
The MIDB is also one of the seven local private banks allowed
to undertake foreign exchange transaction, thus favoring
industrialists in their relative trade activities.
</P>
<P>
In line with the market-oriented economic policy, Myanmar has
reformed its financial system by enacting new banking and
financial institutions law in July 1990 to promote private
sector's economic activities. 
