<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection Station in Qinghai's Unpopulated Hoh Xil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- An environmental protection
station is well established in the unpopulated area of Hoh Xil
near the source of the Yangtze River in Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
Facilities at the station include workshops, with a combined
floor space of over 80 sq. m., a multi-purpose hall with a floor
space of 50 sq. m., a 28-meter-high watchtower, and equipment for
telecommunications, power generating and heating.
</P>
<P>
The station is named after Gyaisang Soinamdaje, a former deputy
Party secretary of Zhidoi County, Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture in
Yushu, who died of protecting the wildlife in Hoh Xil.
</P>
<P>
It was built with donated funds by young volunteer workers,
including a group of college students from Beijing, Qingdao,
Chengdu, Guangzhou, and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Located in the northwestern part of the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau
and with an average elevation of over 5,000 m., Hoh Xil is
considered the largest unpopulated area in China, and a place best
suited for protecting animals in the extremely cold climate unique
to the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau.
</P>
<P>
The area is home to about 250 varieties of mammals, birds and
high-grade plants, and the number of wild animals here is
estimated at between 30,000 and 40,000, including some listed
under state top protection, such as the yak, the Tibetan wild
donkey, the Tibetan antelope, and snow leopards.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the station has created favorable
conditions for protecting the natural environment at the source of
the Yangtze River and for protecting wildlife and plants in Hoh
Xil.
</P>
<P>
It will also help stop illegal hunting and facilitate wildlife
studies, said an official with the Qinghai Provincial Bureau for
Wildlife Protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
