<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Countries Pursue Growth Amid Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Eleven American nations
vowed on Thursday to promote "sustained growth" through sound
fiscal policies in a bid to ward off the economic crises
enveloping Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
In a communique after the first day of their meeting, finance
officials from nine Latin American countries, Canada and the U.S.
said they would pursue "continued macroeconomic stability" and
implement "sound fiscal policies" in order to gain economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The countries -- including Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Colombia,
Ecuador, Mexico, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela -- would also
maintain their current exchange rate policies and regimes, open
capital markets and continue their structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
The communique said, "The external environment has deteriorated
further in recent weeks, especially reflecting market reactions to
the crisis in Russia."
</P>
<P>
The officials agreed on the importance of strategies to better
manage risks associated with the volatility of international
capital flows.
</P>
<P>
"They call upon the international financial institutions to
continue to look at possible ways to respond to such volatility
and to report back on possible strategies and mechanisms," said
the communique.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the two-day meeting at the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) was "to discuss recent global economic
developments and current prospects, their impact on the Western
Hemisphere, and the strategies of the countries in the region to
adapt to the more difficult external environment", it noted.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials were worried that the financial turmoil in
Russia and Asia would extend to Latin America, the so-called
backyard of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the headquarters of IMF earlier in the day, Mexican
Finance Minister Jose Angel Gurria complained that markets were
overreacting to world financial problems.
</P>
<P>
"Markets are certainly overreacting and not discriminating at
all between countries that have done their homework and are taking
care of their fiscal positions, taking care to have a flexible,
modern and responsive exchange rate regime," Gurria said.
</P>
<P>
He denied that the meeting was designed to seek IMF funds to
ward off financial troubles. "We have not come to ask for money.
We have not come here to organize a great fund to support Latin
America."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin told reporters
developments in the Latin America were "profoundly important" to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We have felt from the very beginning ... that what happens in
Latin America is profoundly important for the United States,"
Rubin said. "For that reason, we have been extremely supportive
of the activities and programs in Latin America that deal with the
issue."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said many Latin American countries were equipped to deal
with the world financial situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
