<DOCNO> XIE19980904.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica, Nicaragua Ministers To Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of Costa
Rica and Nicaragua will meet soon to discuss the border dispute
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican Foreign Affairs Minister Roberto Rojas said
Thursday that his Nicaraguan counterpart accepted an invitation to
come to San Jose, and the meeting would be held at the end of next
week.
</P>
<P>
This would be Rojas's first meeting with the Nicaraguan foreign
minister, Eduardo Montealegre, who took the portfolio last
September.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries became tense last month,
when Nicaragua decided to ban the transit of armed Costa Rican
policemen along the border San Juan River, over which it exerts
full sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica has a right to navigate freely on the river, and
this includes, according to its authorities, the transit of
policemen carrying their regulation armaments.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan defense minister and the Costa Rica minister of
public security reached an agreement on the river last July 30,
but the Nicaraguan Foreign Ministry later invalidated that
agreement, which worsened the situation.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican President Miguel Angel Rodriguez said Thursday that
he met last weekend in Puerto Rico with Nicaraguan Vice President
Enrique Bolanos and discussed the issue.
</P>
<P>
"Both of us are collaborating to cool this situation and find
the best solution for Costa Rica," said Rodriguez. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
