<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-Hit Chinese Farmers Preparing To Rebuild Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Liu Yungui, a village woman
from Lixian County in central China's Hunan Province, barely
restrained herself from tears when she saw floodwaters inundating
her house and her pet, a yellow dog.
</P>
<P>
With the help of neighbors and relief workers, Liu managed to
move to a dike along Dongting Lake. Since then, she has tried to
adapt herself to living on the levee, where small shops, barbers
and some other makeshift facilities have been set up.
</P>
<P>
Despite the inconveniences of living on the dike, Liu and her
fellow villagers have been working hard to dry up the crop seeds
they pulled out of the floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
"Just like a climber, we have reached the flat ground after
surmounting a mountain," said Liu. "Now we are sure to defeat the
floods and resume our normal life."
</P>
<P>
Currently, Liu is busy sowing rape seeds on a plot of land she
borrowed from a local farmer near her makeshift lean-to on top of
the dike. She plans to transplant rape seedlings to her own
farmland some two kilometers away once the floods have receded.
</P>
<P>
"Although the government is distributing food every day, we
shouldn't be wholly dependent," said the woman, "and we must do
something to help ourselves and alleviate the burden on the
government."
</P>
<P>
Liu's efforts are a normal sight in the flood-ravaged areas of
the country. While millions of civilians and soldiers are
continuing their battles against the gradually retreating floods,
farmers in some stricken areas are busy preparing to rebuild their
houses and resume production.
</P>
<P>
Wherever it is possible, farmers in these areas are seen
ploughing, sowing, spreading manure and replenishing small-fish
stock. In Lixian county, local villagers have sown 13,000 hectares
of drained land with corn and beans.
</P>
<P>
They have used bulldozers and pumps to reinforce dikes and
drain floodwaters form farmlands, while the Lixian county
government has allocated more than 300,000 yuan to purchase seeds
for various autumn crops for the farmers.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, this year's summer floods, the
worst in China since 1954, have devastated 29 of the country's 31
provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities, claimed 3,004
lives, damaged nearly five million houses, submerged 21 million
hectares of farmlands, and affected a total of more than 223
million people.
</P>
<P>
With the end of the flooding in sight, the task of rebuilding
has already been put on the agenda of the central government. The
State Council has sent special groups to affected areas to assess
the damages and work out plans for reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
During a recent trip to the flooded areas, Premier Zhu Rongji
stressed that rebuilding is not just a duplication of the past,
but should be carried out through scientific and rational
planning.
</P>
<P>
Rebuilding must be aimed at bringing anti-flood capabilities
and economic power in the flood-stricken areas to a higher level,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
In related developments, China's central bank, the People's
Bank of China, has issued an emergency circular, ordering all
domestic financial institutions to assist the rebuilding effort by
providing affected farmers with low-interest loans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
