<HEADLINE> Remote Diagnosis to Be Conducted for Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A vehicle carrying
remote-diagnostic equipment today left Beijing for Wuhan, capital
of central China's Hubei Province. The mobile facility will enable
doctors in Beijing to diagnose patients on the front lines of
flood relief.
</P>
<P>
When the remote-diagnostic vehicle arrives at the dikes along
the Yangtze River, more than 500 doctors and medical experts will
gather in Beijing to diagnose medical problems for patients in the
flooded areas. The system can broadcast the patients' symptoms
live to the medical experts, who can then recommend therapy or
directions for surgery, if needed.  
</P>
