<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Gives More Aid to China's Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Thursday that
it would provide 750,000 Canadian dollars (487,500 U.S.dollars) in
additional emergency relief aid to help flood victims in China.
</P>
<P>
"The massive displacement of people caused by severe flooding
has brought a sense of uncertainty to millions of Chinese," said
International Cooperation Minister Diane Marleau.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy said: "These funds,
together with those of Canadian non-governmental organizations and
the private sector, express the deep concern Canadians feel for
the people of China, now, and as they begin to re-build their
cities and their lives."
</P>
<P>
Canada, through the Canadian International Development Agency
(CICA), will provide 300,000 Canadian dollars (195,000 dollars) to
World Vision Canada to purchase Canadian medicines which will be
distributed by World Vision China to flood victims. An additional
450,000 Canadian dollars (292,500 dollars) will go to the
International Federation of Red Crescent Societies in support of
their efforts to help the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
This new contribution is in addition to the 250,000 Canadian
dollars in aid announced by CIDA earlier this summer, and the
310,000 Canadian dollars in public contributions to the Canadian
Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
These bring Canada's total humanitarian assistance to China's
flood victims to 1.6 million Canadian dollars (1.04 million
dollars) since July, and include additional public contributions
through World Vision Canada and the Canadian Red Cross. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
