<HEADLINE> Chain Stores Expanding Fast in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Chain stores have been
expanding rapidly in China as the number of chain-store businesses
in the country exceeded 1,000 by the end of 1997, with over 15,000
business outlets, according to a recent national retail sales
conference in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
These figures represented 42 percent and 50 percent increases
over 1996 statistics, respectively. These enterprises realized 42
billion yuan in sales last year, according to the conference.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one of these chain store enterprises now have more than
50 retail outlets, and 56 of them are capable of doing over 100
million yuan in sales annually.
</P>
<P>
Chain stores are more developed in major cities like Beijing,
Shanghai, and Guangzhou and in economically advanced coastal areas
where people are more ready to accept this form of shopping.
</P>
<P>
And the types of chain store businesses have expanded from
commercial retailing to services like catering, hotel services,
and tourism.
</P>
<P>
A complete chain-store management mechanism governing new
services, the purchase and distribution of commodities,
operations, marketing and training of personnel, has now formed in
most of these areas.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, more and more transnational chain-store
corporations have chosen China for expansion of their businesses
since the early part of the decade, making competition in China
fiercer and in turn giving impetus to business growth.
</P>
<P>
Xiang Xin, a senior official with the State Economic and Trade
Commission, predicted that the next five to ten years will be
crucial for the growth of China's chain-store businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
