<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Training Benefits Laid-off Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Plunging into "help needed"
classified ads after being laid-off is important, but a little
time for psychological readjustment before that will be beneficial.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily said this is the message being conveyed
during discussions of the ongoing Eighth National Congress of
Chinese Women concerning the much-talked-about topic of laid-off
female workers.
</P>
<P>
Chinese women become mostly affected in this transitory period,
as they represent a considerable proportion of the working force
in chopped sectors such as the textile industry.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, among the 5.77 million registered
laid-off and unemployed workers in China, 52.7 percent were female.
</P>
<P>
With the help of local women's organizations, many have been
re-employed. During the past two years, the All-China Women's
Federation has helped about 480,000 laid-off women find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Most of these jobs are in the tertiary industry, such as
household helpers and community workers, requiring little skills.
</P>
<P>
"Women should break the shackles they have made for themselves
in finding jobs, and state-owned enterprises are not the only
choice," said Qu Sufang, vice-chairperson of the Zhejiang Women's
Federation.
</P>
<P>
Limited education has affected middle-aged women -- the
majority of Chinese laid-off women -- in their competitiveness in
the market place.
</P>
<P>
Women's federations have mainly chosen to help laid-off female
workers by providing them with skill training.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
