<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Courts Pursuing Debtors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's courts recently
launched a mass campaign to ensure debtors cannot repudiate their
obligations, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, 170,000 yuan (20,482 US dollars) in outstanding
debts was repaid in the Fengtai district People's Court, where
many cases were brought for resolution.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Zhongshan, president of the Fengtai District
People's Court, more debt resolution cases cannot be settled in
court each year, with an increase of 30 percent between this year
and last.
</P>
<P>
"The debtors often try every means to conceal their real
financial situations and put off repayment as long as possible,"
said Fang Youquan, the president judge of the settlements
department of Fengtai District People's Court.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday morning, more than 100 debtors appeared before the
Fengtai District People's Court. Some of them placed their hopes
on drawing the sympathies of their creditors before they realized
that the court would not waste time on negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Some turned pale at the announcement of one man's detention by
the court, while others dropped their heads in the light of the
media's cameras.
</P>
<P>
After four debtors were detained, another seven agreed to make
restitution before the court. An old man pulled 30,000 yuan (3,614
US dollars) from his pockets and submitted it to the bench.
</P>
<P>
By 3 p.m. on Wednesday, 22 people had turned over 71,914 yuan
(8,664 US dollars) in cash and 106,230 yuan (12,799 US dollars) in
checks to resolve their outstanding obligations. Seventy percent
of them wrote letters of guarantee to the court, pledging to pay
their debts.
</P>
<P>
"It's a shame to have paid these debts in the presence of so
many members of the media," one man who did not give his name said.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen of the cases were completely resolved and seven cases
were partially settled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
