<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Increasing in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in China
continues to grow despite the impact by the Asian financial crisis,
according to a report by the State Administration for Industry and
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The report, published in a recent edition of the China
Information newspaper, said that China approved 9,196
foreign-invested companies in the first half this year with a
total investment of 28.82 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, China had had 236,400 foreign-invested
businesses, a rise of 0.32 percent over the end of last year, said
the report, while the amount of foreign investment grew 2.29
percent to 770.742 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
As Asian countries decrease their investment in China, American
and European countries are increasing theirs, with North American
countries setting up 1,393 businesses in China in the six-month
period, a year-to-year rise of 12.25 percent, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners also tend to adopt long-term investment strategies
in China, with more money spent on agriculture, transport and
communications, storage and warehousing, posts and
telecommunications, and social services, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
