<HEADLINE> Liquor Donated to Flood-Fighting Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Six leading Chinese liquor
producers have decided to donate over one million bottles of
spirits to soldiers and armed police still fighting the worst
flooding in 40 years along the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
These distilleries, including makers of the brand-named
Wuliangye, Luzhou Laojiao, and Jiannanchun, are all located in
southwest China's Sichuan Province, where the Yangtze flows
through. Previously, they donated huge amounts of
flood relief funds and materials.
</P>
<P>
The 1.1434 million bottles of liquor, weighing 571.7 tons and
valued at 34.68 million yuan (about 4.2 million U.S. dollars),
will express high respect and sincere gratitude from the 80
million Sichuan people to the 270,000 flood-fighting soldiers and
armed policemen, said a spokesman of the provincial government,
who suggested and mobilized the liquor donation.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan is one of China's major liquor production bases,
and has one of China's largest liquor-drinking populations.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the six leading distilleries turned out a combined
340,000 tons of spirits, with sales amounting to 8.3 billion yuan,
and pre-tax profits of 3.1 billion yuan. 
</P>
