<HEADLINE> Sacked Malaysian Deputy PM Expelled from Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's ruling United
Malays National Organization (UMNO) Friday expelled former Deputy
Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim from the party.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister and UMNO President Mahathir Mohamad
announced the decision taken by the UMNO Supreme Council at its
four-hour meeting here which ended at about 1 am Friday.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who was sacked as Deputy Prime Minister and Finance
Minister on Wednesday, attended the meeting as UMNO deputy
president and was given an opportunity to defend himself against
allegations leveled at him. He left the meeting about 15 minutes
before it ended.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision at a news conference attended by all
the council members who were at the meeting, Mahathir said "This
is to show that the council's decision was a consensus that all
members supported the decision without exception," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked by reporters why Anwar was expelled from the party,
Mahathir said he need not give reasons as it was a party matter.
</P>
<P>
"The decision was made after Anwar was given ample
opportunities to explain the allegations brought against him," he
said, adding all Supreme Council members who attended the meeting
were also given a chance to express their views before voting.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that following Anwar's expulsion, the deputy
president's post would be left vacant until next year's party
elections and that the post of Deputy Prime Minister would most
likely not be filled.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that he would be the Acting Finance Minister for
the time being.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on Anwar's claims that there was a
conspiracy at the highest level to ruin him, Mahathir said: "That
is his right to make allegations. You have to prove it, I think he
will be given an opportunity in a proper forum".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Anwar told his supporters after the council meeting
he was innocent and was not prepared to leave UMNO or resign as
party deputy president.
</P>
<P>
"I know they'll continue to run me down through the local media
with the wildest of allegations. "I'll have to fight to the end,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In several affidavits filed at the High Court Thursday, Anwar
was alleged to have been involved in sexual improprieties,
undermining national security, leaking national secrets and
accepting bribes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
