<HEADLINE> Venus Williams Patches up Patch Problems with WTA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Venus Williams of the
United States, world number 5 player and runner-up last year,
attached the tiny rectangular logo to the shoulder strap of her
lime-green outfit in the second round match today at the U.S.
Open tennis championships in New York.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old fashion designer had to pay 100 U.S. dollars
for failing to wear a WTA patch in her opener. She beat qualifier
Anne Kremer 6-1, 6-3 easily today.
</P>
<P>
Williams faced a $500 fine if she did not display the patch
Thursday. The fines would have escalated to $ 25,000 had she
continued to pass on the patch.
</P>
<P>
"It just seems I am always in the middle of controversy, so it
is nothing new for me," she said. "I am separate from those type
of things. Generally, I do my practicing and I play tennis."
</P>
<P>
WTA orders players to wear the logo as part of its sponsorship
contract. Only Nike players are exempted from the patch
requirement because of a company policy that predates the WTA
deal.
</P>
<P>
Reebok, which has a multimillion dollar sneaker and clothing
contract with Williams, designed a seven outfit wardrobe for her
at the Open and defended the logo-less look, arguing that wearing
one would violate the company's agreement with her.
</P>
<P>
Williams overpowered Kremer today with her big
serve-and-volley match. Her serve reached at speeds up to 117
mph, the fastest for women players in the world.
</P>
<P>
"Everything is going very well," Williams said. "I think
everything is solid. I am trying to work more on serve and
volley,and some coming into the net more. I would definitely like
to play better."
</P>
<P>
She needed only 58 minutes to beat Kremer. "My matches haven't
been too tough so far. I think tougher your match, maybe the
better you play. I just want to make sure that I am doing what I
should on every point and not losing any focus," she said.
</P>
