<HEADLINE> Hingis Advances to Third Round of U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Top seed and defending
champion Martina Hingis of Switzerland survived a shaky first set
to beat 1997 French Open champion Iva Majoli of Croatia today in
the second round of the 14 million U.S. dollars U.S. Open tennis
championships in New York.
</P>
<P>
Hingis was pushed to a tie-breaker in the first set before
responding with a 7-6 (7-4), 6-0 victory. The unseeded Majoli
defeated Hingis in last year's French Open final. Hingis will
play 18-year-old Amelie Mauresmo of France in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't feel like I controlled the game," said Hingis, who
has won six of eight career matches against Majoli. "I was just
very nervous the first set. I was still also in the second. I
kind of loosened up and everything started to go in."
</P>
<P>
Hingis, who captured three of four Grand Slam titles last
year,is looking to recapture her early-season form. She started
1997 strong, defending her Australian Open crown and picking up
three other titles. But Hingis has not won a title since May and
her 3,000-point lead for the No. 1 ranking has shrunk to just 500.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss teenager broke Majoli's serve in the fourth game of
the first set but the 20-year-old Croatian broke back in the
seventh game. Both players held serve as the set went to a
tie-break, wich Hingis won when Majoli's forehand went wide.
</P>
<P>
Dropping the set appeared to deflate Majoli, who won just 12
points in the second set.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't let her back in the game," Hingis said. "I was
forced from the first game on. She would serve -- by 30-Love up
-- and I still kind of came back and won the game."
</P>
<P>
Fifth seed Venus Williams moved easily into the third round
with a 6-1, 6-3 victory over qualifier Anne Kremer of Luxembourg.
Fourth seed and 1994 winner Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain beat
Colombian Fabiola Zuluaga 6-3, 6-2. No. 13 Amanda Coetzer of
South Africa downed Raluca Sandu of Romania 6-0, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
In the men's section, sixth seed Greg Rusedski of Britain
ousted Bohdan Ulihrach of the Czech Republic 6-4, 3-6, 6-4, 2-6,
7-5.Seventh seed Alex Corretja of Spain beat Italy's Gianluca
Pozzi 2-6,6-3, 7-5, 7-5 in a first round match completed today.
</P>
<P>
Eighth seed American Andre Agassi, the 1994 champion, was
fully stretched in a five-set battle before edging Guillaume
Raoux of France 6-3, 6-5, 6-7 (6-8), 3-6, 6-1. No. 9 Karol Kucera
of Slovakia downed France's Jerome Golmard 7-5, 6-3, 6-0, and No.
12 Jonas Bjorkman of Sweden beat American Jonathan Stark 6-2,
6-3, 6-1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
