<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are the
major economic news briefs from Latin American countries for the
past few days:
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil has been losing an average of one billion
dollars a day from its international reserves in the last two
weeks, which amounted to more than 70 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The "Folha de Sao Paulo" newspaper reported Thursday that these
reserves are now a little above 60 billion dollars, so the
Brazilian government is bound to adopt stronger measures to
contain the depletion of its international reserves.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The investment foreseen for the next ten years in
the Pequiven Petrochemicals firm business plan will be 8.3 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The firm could expand its capital, according to the law, by
going public in the stock market for the development of the
projects including the production of fertilizer, methanol,
oleofines, and their byproducts.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan petrochemical industry is the third source of
hard currency in the industrial field and represents 15 percent of
the non-oil exports.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's unemployment rate reached 6.4 percent
during the May-July 1998 period, according to data from the
National Statistics Institute.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment in the 15-19 years olds range was three times
the national index (20.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
The sectors with the highest range of unemployment were gas,
electricity, water, mines and manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Interamerican Development Bank (IADB) since
opening business has invested some 70 billion dollars in
development projects in 26 Latin American countries, said its
representative in Mexico Bolivar Santacruz.
</P>
<P>
According to the representative, Mexico has received 12 billion
dollars in credits for development projects in water, drainage and
electrification. The IADB will grant Mexico loans worth 900
million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
