<HEADLINE> Tight Security in Place for Athletics World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Security at the
athletics World Cup to be held in Johannesburg next week will be
the biggest operation of its kind mounted for a sporting event in
South Africa,South African officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nobody need to worry about his or her security at the World
Cup as tight security measures are being taken to ensure the
safety of all athletes and spectators, a top security official of
the Gauteng province, where Johannesburg is located, said.
</P>
<P>
Local police will join hands with national police and defense
force in the operation, which will be controlled from a center
within the Johannesburg Stadium, the venue of the competition.
</P>
<P>
Medical, traffic and private security people will also be
under command of the controlling center.
</P>
<P>
Many of the world's leading track and field stars will
participate in the eighth International Amateur Athletics
Federation (IAAF) World Cup in Athletics from September 11 to 13.
</P>
<P>
But worries have been voiced over the security of competitors
after a bomb blast in a Cape Town restaurant last week, which
claimed two lives and left 26 injured.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the fears are a string of bomb scares which have
been received during the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) summit
currently under way in Durban, a seaport in eastern South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The United States Athletics Federation, concerned about the
safety of its team, is reportedly considering a withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Danie Malan, chairman of the event's coordinating committee,
said a safe World Cup must be guaranteed as it would affect other
sporting bodies' decisions when considering bringing events to
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The eyes of the sporting world will be on the World Cup...The
events next week will influence other sporting institutions which
may be looking at staging major international tournaments in
South Africa,such as the World Cup soccer," Malan said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is one of the favorite candidates expected to
host the 2006 World Cup soccer. Germany and Britain are also
bidding to host the event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
