<HEADLINE> Australian, U.S. Study Finds Lead Risk in Mothers' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Lead which has accumulated in
a woman's bones can be released during pregnancy and transfered to
breast milk during lactation, according to the result of an
Australian and U.S. study released here Friday.
</P>
<P>
That can cause increased exposures for breast-fed infants whose
mothers have a long-term history of lead exposure, the Australia's
Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organization
(CSIRO) said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The study, by Australian and American scientists, appeared in
the latest on-line version of the October issue of Environmental
Health Perspectives, the monthly journal of the National Institute
of Environmental Health Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"Breast feeding is still an important option for healthy
mothers," said Brian Gulson, a CSIRO toxicologist.
</P>
<P>
"Breast-fed infants are only at risk if the mother has been
previously exposed to high concentration of lead from external
sources such as leaded paint, pottery, or, in many other
countries, industrial sources and leaded gasoline."
</P>
<P>
Excessive lead is harmful to the development of children's
health, particularly to their intelligence development.
</P>
<P>
Previous research has demonstrated that lead is stored in
bones, but scientists could not quantify its release into the
blood and other bodily fluids.
</P>
<P>
To answer the question, the Australian and U.S. scientists
compared second-generation Australian women with women who had
migrated to Australia from Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Lead found in Eastern Europe has a slightly different atomic
weight from lead found in Australia, so scientists were able to
differentiate between skeletal lead deposits that had accumulated
from the immigrants' earlier exposures while in their native
country, and more recent exposure.
</P>
<P>
Earlier data from the same study had shown that as much as
40-70 percent of the blood lead in pregnant women can come from
lead that has accumulated in the bones.
</P>
<P>
Because the study participants' blood lead concentrations were
relatively low, most had values less than 5 micrograms lead per
deciliter of blood and the lead concentrations in their breast
milk were also low, 0.7 parts per billion on average.
</P>
<P>
These concentrations were not significantly different from
those found in various kinds of infant formulae.
</P>
<P>
In spite of these low concentrations, the researchers found a
strong correlation between the amount of lead in the mothers' milk
samples and the corresponding blood lead levels of the infants.
</P>
<P>
Calculations based on the first 60 to 90 days postpartum
indicated that 36-80 percent of the infants' total blood lead was
coming from breast milk or formula.
</P>
<P>
The study also produced preliminary evidence suggesting that
calcium supplementation can have a protective effect by slowing
the release of lead from skeletal stores.
</P>
<P>
The Australian researchers are planning additional studies to
determine calcium's effectiveness in pregnant and nursing mothers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
