<HEADLINE> Hoddle Stalls on Contract Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- England manager Glenn Hoddle
told the Football Association (FA) that he wanted to delay talks
on extending his contract.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle's current contract runs until the European
Championships and the FA want him to agree an extension until the
World Cup in 2002.
</P>
<P>
FA chairman Keith Wiseman confirmed: "Glenn has said he does
not want to talk at the moment.
</P>
<P>
"Glenn's perspective, which is one I can understand very
easily,is that `I'm not sure whether I want to make a final de
cision about it now when it's still got two years to go'."
</P>
<P>
Hoddle is in the middle of a rocky period as England coach.
The row over his controversial World Cup Diary had only just died
down when he came in for criticism in another book, written by
Arsenal's England defender Tony Adams.
</P>
<P>
The England team flew off to Sweden on Thursday ahead of their
first European Championship qualifier in Stockholm on
Saturday.
</P>
