<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Card Given to Breakaway Super League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The breakaway European Super
League was given a red card on Thursday when England's 20 Premier
League clubs agreed unanimously that any new European League
should be run under the auspices of UEFA, European soccer's gover
ning body.
</P>
<P>
The English clubs also expressed doubt that the financial plan
outlined by Media Partners, the organisation promoting the new
league,was viable. They said that any future negotiations would
be carried out by the premier league and not by individual clubs.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United, Liverpool and Arsenal had been in
discussion with Media Partners as recently as Monday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Media Partners and Gerhard Aigner, UEFA's
general secretary, addressed a meeting of the premier league
clubs' chairmen on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chief executive Peter Leaver said afterwards: "The meeting
listened very carefully to both presentations and noted the
points made.
</P>
<P>
"There was clear, unanimous opposition to the suggestion of a
breakaway but it was agreed that reform of the European club
competitions was needed.
</P>
<P>
"The clubs stressed that playing under the current governing
bodies was very important and that the future of the European
competitions would be through UEFA."
</P>
<P>
The clubs also rejected the central tenet of Media
Partners'plan that half of the 36 Super League clubs would be
guaranteed a place for three years based on their performance
during the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting stressed the importance of the integrity of
domestic competitions and were absolutely firm on the need for
European qualification to be based on sporting merit from the
previous season only," said Leaver.
</P>
<P>
Rodolfo Hecht, head of Media Partners, said on Wednesday that
the new league would triple the income of participating teams.
</P>
<P>
But Leaver said he had "very grave doubts" about their ability
to generate those figures.
</P>
<P>
Premier league spokesman Mike Lee added that the clubs "were
not convinced" by the answers given by Media Partners to
questions about its financial model.
</P>
<P>
Despite the reservations, however, Leaver said the clubs
accepted that there were going to be major changes in European
competition.
</P>
<P>
In something of a contradiction to his earlier statement, he
said: "We are not ruling anything in and not ruling anything
out. We have a blank piece of paper."
</P>
<P>
The clubs said they would now await the report of UEFA's Task
Force, of which Leaver is a member.
</P>
<P>
The Task Force will make an initial report to UEFA's executive
committee meeting on October 6 with a view to preparing a
concrete proposal by the next meeting on December 10.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Media Partners had a different view of the
meeting, saying: "The premier league was very keen to become
involved in the European Football League project.
</P>
<P>
"This is the clubs' project and we are delighted to welcome
the premier league into the discussions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
