<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Finds European Executives Wary of E-commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, September 3 (Xinhua) -- In a study of European senior
executives released Wednesday, a global consulting organization has
found the greatest barrier to the continent's success in the emerging
electronic economy is a hesitancy among the business leaders there.
</P>
<P>
According to Andersen Consulting, despite their enthusiasm for the
future potential of e-commerce, European executives are still standing
on the sidelines, jeopardizing the continent's long-term
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
In a survey of more than 300 European senior executives between
December 1997 and July 1998, Andersen found only 39 percent are taking
steps to incorporate e-commerce into their current operations and
strategies, although 82 percent of them believe that e-commerce will
have a strategic impact on their businesses in the future.
Furthermore, only 19 percent of them regard e-commerce as a serious
competitive threat to their business today.
</P>
<P>
Andersen suggested several causes for the hesitation. Half of
respondents blamed a lack of consumer understanding about e-commerce.
A majority see privacy, security and the lack of regulatory framework
as key barriers. More than 80 percent cite the need for governments to
work together for a common international framework.
</P>
<P>
Still, the study identified several European advantages in Net
commerce, including the broad use of smart cards -- credit card-sized
plastic cards with a computer chip embedded. Smart cards are seen as
both a security device and a way to store personal data or electronic
cash. Andersen also cites Europe's lead in use of digital mobile
telephone and a strong position in e-commerce applications for digital
TV and Web phones.
</P>
<P>
The burgeoning worldwide potential for e-commerce is obvious,
Andersen said in the report. In the past five years, it said, the
Internet has surged from a network of 3 million predominately
U.S.-based users to a commercial mass medium with more than 100
million users worldwide, including more than 25 million across Europe.
Worldwide e-commerce is currently estimated at about 10 billion U.S.
dollars and is expected to reach 500 billion dollars by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Urging quick action, Andersen outlined recommendations for both the
European governments and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Andersen said, European governments need to work with
businesses to create a regulatory regime that facilitates global
e-commerce, encourages new venture capital markets, adopts e-commerce
itself, ensure adequate training and retraining, and promotes
-commerce with both business and the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
