<HEADLINE> Senate Democrat Calls Clinton's Behavior "Immoral" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Democratic Senator Joseph
Lieberman on Thursday called U.S. President Bill Clinton's
behavior in the Monica Lewinsky scandal "immoral," but said
Congress should withhold action on it until the full story is
known.
</P>
<P>
In a Senate floor speech Lieberman said Clinton's behavior was
"immoral," "harmful" and deserves public rebuke.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Lieberman said it is premature for Congress
to take any action before Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr
submits a report to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
"While the legal process moves forward, it is important that we
provide the president with the time and space and support he needs
to carry out his most important duties and protect our national
interest and security," said Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
"The conduct the president admitted to that night was serious
and his assumption of responsibility inadequate," Lieberman said
of Clinton's August 17 nationally televised confession of his
affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
Lieberman said Clinton's behavior may have "jeopardized his
administration's historic record of accomplishment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
