<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney General Reviewing Clinton Campaign-Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno is reviewing whether to seek an independent counsel to
investigate fund-raising activities in President Bill Clinton's
re-election campaign in 1996, Justice Department officials said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reno is specifically considering whether so-called issue ads
televised during Clinton's 1996 campaign violated federal
campaign-spending laws and limits.
</P>
<P>
"There is a review of new information regarding issue advocacy
in the 1996 election," Justice Department spokesman Bert
Brandenburg said of the almost two-year White House fund-raising
allegation.
</P>
<P>
Republicans in the Senate have charged that Clinton and his top
political aides controlled the 44 million dollars in advertising
that was paid for by the Democratic Party, but was aimed at
advancing Clinton's re-election effort, circumventing the spending
limits on individual campaigns.
</P>
<P>
At a weekly Justice Department news conference, Reno said, "All
I can say is we have new information that I cannot comment on."
</P>
<P>
James Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House counsel's
office, defended the use of the issue ads as "entirely legal and
appropriate."
</P>
<P>
He said, "The ads focused on real issues before Congress and
the American people and they made clear the differences between
Democrats and Republicans on balancing the budget, Medicare,
welfare and other policy concerns. They were cleared by legal
counsel."
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Kennedy said, "There was no violation of
campaign spending limits. We are confident that, at the end of its
review, the Justice Department will arrive at a fair conclusion
based on the facts and the law."
</P>
<P>
Democrats have complained that Robert Dole's presidential
campaign and the Republican Party in 1996 used similar tactics to
get around federal spending limits.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the review focused only on the Democrats or
covered the Republicans as well, Reno replied, "We're following
every lead."
</P>
<P>
Reno, who has been under immense political pressure from
Republicans in Congress to hand over the investigation to an
independent counsel, said she would make her decision based on
what the law requires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
