<HEADLINE> Clinton Leaves Northern Ireland for Dublin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
wound up a whirlwind morale-boosting tour of Northern Ireland and
left for Dublin Thursday night to continue his visit to the Irish
Republic.
</P>
<P>
Before he started off, Clinton was given a rapturous reception
by thousands in the ancient cathedral town of Armagh, the
spiritual home of Irish Protestants and Catholics alike.
</P>
<P>
He said the province's achievement in drawing a line under
three decades of sectarian bloodshed was a beacon for other areas
of conflict from the Middle East to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
"When I go now to other trouble spots, I point to you as proof
that peace is not an idle daydream. For your peace is real. It
resonates around the world and echoes in the ears of people hungry
for an end to strife in their own countries," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
An impassioned Clinton said his message to politicians locked
in seemingly intractable conflicts was the same the world over:
"Do not tell me it has to be this way -- look at Northern
Ireland... a new day has dawned!"
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his wife Hillary, accompanied by British Prime
Minister Tony Blair and his wife Cherie, earlier visited Omagh to
meet with survivors and relatives of those killed by the bomb on
August 15. Twenty-eight died and 220 injured in the deadliest
atrocity in Northern Ireland's 30-year conflict.
</P>
<P>
While in Omagh, Clinton unveiled a black-draped golden plaque
commemorating the dead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
